# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: accordion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:accordion/accompaniment] The accompaniment for a vocal melody or instrumental solo can be played by a single musician playing an instrument such as piano, pipe organ, or guitar.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] A solo singer can accompany themself by playing guitar or piano while they sing, and in some rare cases, a solo singer can even accompany themself just using their voice and body (e.g., Bobby McFerrin).
[src:accordion/accompaniment] With choral music, the accompaniment to a vocal solo can be provided by other singers in the choir, who sing harmony parts or countermelodies.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] An **accompanist** is a musician who plays an accompaniment part.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] Accompanists often play keyboard instruments (e.g., piano, pipe organ, synthesizer) or, in folk music and traditional styles, a guitar.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] While sight-reading (the ability to play a notated piece of music without preparing it) is important for many types of musicians, it is essential for professional accompanists.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] In auditions for musical theater and orchestras, an accompanist will often have to sight read music.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] A number of classical pianists have found success as accompanists rather than soloists; arguably the best known example is Gerald Moore, well known as a Lieder accompanist.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] The term *accompanist* also refers to a musician (typically a pianist) who plays for singers, dancers, and other performers at an audition or rehearsal—but who does not necessarily participate in the ensemble that plays for the final performance (which might be an orchestra or a big band).
[src:accordion/accompaniment] Notated accompaniment may be indicated obbligato (obliged) or ad libitum (at one's pleasure).
[src:accordion/accompaniment] The accompaniment instrumentalists and/or singers can be provided with a fully notated accompaniment part written or printed on sheet music.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] This is the norm in Classical music and in most large ensemble writing (e.g., orchestra, pit orchestra, choir).
[src:accordion/accompaniment] To achieve a stylistic correct sound the accompaniment pattern should remind or imitate the original version using similar rhythms and patterns.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] Chord-playing musicians (e.g., those playing guitar, piano, Hammond organ, etc.) can improvise chords, "fill-in" melodic lines and solos from the chord chart.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] It is rare for chords to be fully written out in music notation in pop and traditional music.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] Some guitarists, bassists and other stringed instrumentalists read accompaniment parts using tabulature (or "tab"), a notation system which shows the musician where on the instrument to play the notes.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] Drummers can play accompaniment by following the lead sheet, a sheet music part in music notation, or by playing by ear.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] In pop and traditional music, bass players, which may be upright bass or electric bass, or another instrument, such as bass synth, depending on the style of music, are usually expected to be able to improvise a bassline from a chord chart or learn the song from a recording.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] In some cases, an arranger or composer may give a bassist a bass part that is fully written out in music notation.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] In some arranged music parts, there is a mix of written-out accompaniment and improvisation.
[src:accordion/accompaniment] For example, in a big band bass part, the introduction and melody ("head") to a tune may have a fully notated bassline, but then for the improvised solos, the arranger may just write out chord symbols (e.g., Bb G7/c min F7), with the expectation that the bassist improvise her own walking bass part.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] An **accordion concerto** is a solo concerto for solo accordion and symphony orchestra or chamber orchestra.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] The accordion concerto has its origin in the twentieth century, following examples as the much older piano concerto or the violin concerto.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] The instrument accordion developed to a full concert instrument, more and more composers started composing for this instrument, also for accordion and orchestra.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In 1937 the first concerto for accordion and orchestra was written by Feodosiy Rubtsov (1904–1986) and performed by Pavel Gvozdev in the Hall of the Leningrad Philharmonic.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In Germany one of the first concertos was written by Hugo Herrmann in 1940 (and a second one in 1948).
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In 1941 two American accordionists wrote and premiered concertos: Anthony Galla-Rini composed Concerto no.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] 1, Andy Arcari wrote his Concerto in D minor.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Accordionist and Italian immigrant Pietro Deiro wrote a concerto in 1946, American composer Roy Harris composed his concerto (in the form of Theme and Variations) in 1947.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Czech composer Emil František Burian wrote an accordion concerto already in 1949.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In 1959 Czech composer Václav Trojan wrote "Pohádky" (fairy tales), which is still often played, in 2013 recorded by Ksenija Sidorova.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] The first female accordion virtuoso to play an accordion concerto with accompaniment from a full symphony orchestra was Adeline Marie Mantino (later Rogillio), shortly following her graduation from the New England Conservatory of Music in 1950.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] The symphony was the Boston Philharmonic Orchestra.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Miss Mantino went on to play with the New York Philharmonic Orchestra and the Boston Pops before settling into a career teaching music, first in Warren, RI and then Woonsocket, RI.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] A very important accordionist for the development of the instrument was Mogens Ellegaard from Denmark.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] He worked together with the Danish composer Ole Schmidt.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] His composition Symphonic Fantasy and Allegro op.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Other Scandinavian composers like Torbjörn Lundquist, Niels Viggo Bentzon (1963) and Per Nørgård (1968) followed.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Arne Nordheim wrote his famous concerto "Spur" in 1975.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In the United States concertos were written by Alan Hovhaness (1959), Henry Cowell (Concerto Brevis, 1960), Carmelo Pino (Concertino, 1964), Paul Creston (1960 & 1964) en Carmine Coppola (1973).
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In 1962 French composer Jean Wiener wrote his concerto for accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In 1972 British composer Gordon Jacob wrote an accordion concerto.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In addition, several virtuoso instrumentalists adopted the classical concerto form in order to demonstrate the wide ranging orchestral sounds of the solo Free bass system instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Included in this group was the Italian-American John Serry Sr., who completed his Concerto for Free Bass Accordion in 1964 for the *Bassetti Accordion* as designed by Julio Giuliette.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Thanks to efforts of leading accordionists like Friedrich Lips, Joseph Macerollo, Geir Draugsvoll, Stefan Hussong, Mie Miki, Ksenija Sidorova and Teodoro Anzellotti the repertoire is growing to more than two hundred compositions.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] Famous composers like Sofia Gubaidulina, Jukka Tiensuu, Kalevi Aho, Giya Kancheli, Toshio Hosokawa, Jesús Torres, Fazil Say and Peter Machajdik wrote accordion concertos.
[src:accordion/accordion-concerto] In 2016 Russian composer Sergei Slonimsky gave an accordion concerto to performers.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion is in a wide variety of musical genres, mainly in traditional and popular music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In some regions, such as in Europe and North America, it has become mainly restricted to traditional, folk and ethnic music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Nonetheless, the button accordion (melodeon) and the piano accordion are widely taught and played in Ireland, and have remained a steady fixture within Irish traditional music, both in Ireland and abroad, particularly in the United States and Great Britain.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Accordions are also played within other Celtic styles (such as in Scotland, Cornwall and Brittany), as well as in English traditional music, American traditional music, polka, Galician folk music, and Eastern European folk music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In other regions, such as Mexico and Latin America, the instrument is very popular in genres like Norteño, Conjunto, and corridos; in Brazil, it is a fixture in popular music styles, such as Sertanejo and Forró.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion is also used in Western art music, such as jazz (most famously the North American accordionist Frank Marocco) and classical music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] After the invention of the accordion in 1829, its popularity spread throughout the world, in no small measure due to the polka craze.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] "Once the polka became a craze in Paris and London during the spring of 1844, it diffused rapidly to the rest of the world. . . .
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In March 1844, polka-mania took Paris: common people, servants, workers and, one assumes, anyone else who wasn't too stuffy were dancing the polka in the streets of the capital and soon in Bordeaux and other French cities as well.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] A week or so later it took London by storm.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Except for a brief moment in time during the 1830s and 1840s when the accordion was heard by French aristocracy during Salon music concerts, the instrument has always been associated with the common people.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion was spread across the globe by the waves of Europeans who emigrated to various parts of the world in the late 19th century and early 20th century.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The mid-19th-century accordion became a favorite of folk musicians for several reasons: "The new instrument's popularity [among the common masses] was a result of its unique qualities.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Firstly, it was much louder than all the older folk instruments put together.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It could easily be heard in even the wildest pub above the stomping of dancing feet.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It was also the prototype of a 'one man band' with bass and chords on the left-hand side and buttons for the melody on the right, and you could still sing along and beat the rhythm with your feet.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The instrument needed no tuning and was always ready to play, but the most ingenious thing about the early one-row squeezebox was that you couldn't play it really badly.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Since its invention, the accordion has become popularly integrated into a lot of varying traditional music styles all over the world, ranging from the European polka and the Colombian Vallenato to Korean trot music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] See the list of traditional music styles that incorporate the accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It is a traditional instrument in Brazilian music, specifically baião of the northeast.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Luiz Gonzaga is called the king of baião.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion is featured heavily in traditional Egyptian music, particularly baladi styles.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Sometimes, certain traditional music styles may even be tied to a certain type of accordion, like the Schrammel accordion for Schrammelmusik, the Trikitixa for Basque music, or the diatonic button accordion in Mexican conjunto and norteño music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It would be hard to name one country in which the accordion did not play a significant role in its music tradition.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It has even been idealized in literature.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion was heard frequently in popular music beginning around 1910 until about 1960.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] With rise of the popularity of the guitar (in particular the electric guitar) and rock music, the popularity of the accordion in pop music in Europe and North-America declined strongly.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In some countries however, such as Brazil and Mexico, the accordion continues to be a fixture in pop music and its popularity is undiminished.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] This half century is often called the "Golden Age of the Accordion." Three players, more than any others, inaugurated this era of popularity for the instrument, all Italian immigrants to the United States: Pietro Frosini, and the two brothers Count Guido Deiro and Pietro Deiro.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] All three players were celebrities on the Vaudeville circuits and performed throughout North America, Europe and Australia during the age of Vaudeville.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] They recorded hundreds of 78 RPM records for the Victor Talking Machine Company, Columbia Records, Decca Records, Edison Records and Cylinders, and other labels.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Guido Deiro was the most successful and famous accordionist during the 1910s and 1920s, and lived a life filled with celebrity, luxury, fast cars, and fast women.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Many popular bands, such as the Paul Whiteman Orchestra, employed staff accordionists.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] After most Vaudeville theaters closed during the Great Depression, accordionists still found work during the 1930s teaching and performing for radio.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Charles Magnante is considered one of the greatest American popular accordionists.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] At the peak of his career, he played 30 live radio broadcasts and eight studio sessions each week.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Another great popular American accordionist was Dick Contino, who toured with the Horace Heidt Orchestra and was billed as the "world's greatest accordion player." He appeared on The Ed Sullivan Show a record 48 times.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In addition, John Serry, Sr. achieved national recognition on tour with Shep Fields and His Rippling Rhythm jazz orchestra during the 1930s, concertized on the CBS radio and television networks in the 1940s and 1950s and appeared in the Broadway Theatre during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] During the 1950s through the 1980s the accordion received great exposure on television with performances by Myron Floren—the accordionist with Lawrence Welk—on *the Lawrence Welk Show*.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] However, with the advent of rock 'n roll and the generation gap in the late 1950s and early 1960s, the accordion declined in popularity, as the younger generation considered it "square"— epitomizing the light-hearted music of their parents and grandparents.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In the United States, it has often been thought of as a "European instrument," despite the accordion having a presence in American music ever since its creation.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Because of this, the accordion has often been the subject of "dumb Euro" stereotypes (portraying Central and Eastern European people as goofy or unintelligent), although modern performers are working to change that stereotype.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In Europe and North American (outside of Mexico), in contemporary mainstream pop music, the use of the accordion is usually considered exotic or old-fashioned.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Nevertheless, some popular acts do use the instrument in their distinctive sounds, and a 2014 Los Angeles Times article reports that the instrument is growing in popularity locally.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] (See the list of popular music acts that incorporate the accordion.) Since the late 19th century, Tejano music has emerged as one of the leading genres for the instrument in America.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Pioneers such as Narciso Martínez gave the instrument staple in the cultural music of Mexican American people.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Central to the evolution of early Tejano music was the blend of traditional forms such as the Corrido and Mariachi, and Continental European styles, such as Polka, introduced by German and Czech settlers in the late 19th century.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In particular, the accordion was adopted by Tejano folk musicians at the turn of the 20th century, and it became a popular instrument for amateur musicians in Texas and Northern Mexico.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion is popular among folk punk and folk rock bands who perform music from countries that often use the accordion, such as in the subgenres of celtic punk and gypsy punk.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Such bands include The Dreadnoughts, Gogol Bordello, the Zydepunks, and Flogging Molly.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion has been a primary instrument in Mexican music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It is mostly associated with Norteño music, which has become one of the most popular music genres in Mexico since the 1990s, but the instrument is also featured in other genres such as Cumbia.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Ramón Ayala is arguably the best-known accordion player in Mexico; nicknamed the "King of the accordion", Ayala has recorded over 113 albums since the 1960s.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Additionally, the accordion became a fixture in merengue music, a genre that is representative of the Dominican Republic.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In some countries, such as Brazil, the accordion is a fixture in mainstream popular music (evidenced by mainstream groups such as Falamansa, Michel Teló, Avioes do Forró).
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The instrument is commonly learned by teenagers and enjoys a popularity comparable to the guitar.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In some regions (such as the North-East, where it is called *sanfona*), the accordion surpasses the guitar in popularity among the youth.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In Brazil, however, the accordion uses normally a very dry tuning, which dissociates it from the wetter sound found in European folk music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The instrument was also used in the Disney song "Whale of a Tale" from *20,000 Leagues Under the Sea*, as well as Donald Duck's song, "Quack Quack Quack".
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It was used in a Christmas setting for the song "Nuttin' for Christmas".
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The composer Tomohito Nishiura frequently uses the accordion in the *Professor Layton* series of games, for example in "Laboratory" or "Don Paolo's Theme".
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] However, when 'Live Versions' of the soundtracks are released, the accordion is occasionally replaced (such as in "London 3" from *Professor Layton and the Unwound Future*).
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Every 'theme' for a game uses the accordion in some capacity.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Various folk metal and viking metal bands, such as Finsterforst, Finntroll, and Turisas that have formed in the 1990s and first decade of the 21st century feature accordions.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Although the accordion is best known primarily as a folk instrument, it has been used with increasing frequency by classical composers.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The earliest surviving concert piece written for the accordion is **Thême varié très brillant pour accordéon methode Reisner**, written in 1836 by Miss Louise Reisner of Paris, an accordionist and amateur composer.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The Russian composer Piotr Ilyitch Tchaikovsky included four optional single-action diatonic accordions in his *Orchestral Suite No.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] 53* (1883), simply to add a little color to the third movement: *Scherzo burlesque*.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The Italian composer Umberto Giordano included the single-action diatonic accordion in his opera *Fedora* (1898).
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordionist appears on-stage—along with a folk-trio consisting of a piccolo player and triangle player—three times in the third act (which is set in Switzerland), to accompany a short and simple song which is sung by a little *Savoyard* (Alpine shepherd).
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In 1915, the American composer Charles Ives included a chorus of diatonic accordions (or concertinas)—along with two pianos, celesta, harp, organ, zither and an optional theremin—in his *Orchestral Set No.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion part—written for the right-hand only—consists of eighteen measures at the very end of the eighteen-minute-long three-movement work.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] All the above works were written for the diatonic button accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The first composer to write specifically for the chromatic accordion (able to play all 12 notes of the chromatic scale) was Paul Hindemith.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In 1921 he included the harmonium in *Kammermusik* No.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] 1, a chamber work in four movements for twelve players, but later rewrote the harmonium part for accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Other German composers also wrote for the accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In 1922, Austrian composer Alban Berg included a short on-stage accordion part in his landmark opera Wozzeck, Op.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The instrument—marked *Ziehharmonika bzw.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In 1937 the first accordion concerto was written and played in Russia.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In the halls of academe, the American concert accordionist Robert Davine played a central role in establishing one of the few major academic courses of study in Accordion Performance within the United States during the late 1950s.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] As the founder and Dean of the University of Denver's Lamont School of Music's Department of Accordion, Davine influenced generations of students both in the United States and the People's Republic of China where he taught Master Classes.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In addition to composing a *Divertimento for Flute, Clarinet and Accordion*, Davine is credited with concertizing and recording extensively within a variety of classical orchestral ensembles including: symphonic orchestras, chamber orchestras as well as string quartets.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] During the 1960s, the American Accordionists Association (AAA) commissioned the Italian American composer Nicolas Flagello to compose an *Introduction and Scherzo* (1964) for solo accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Composers found the free-bass accordion much more attractive and easier to write for as it liberated the instrument from a limited range of bass notes (only a major seventh, C to B) and the pre-set chord buttons.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Despite being invented as early as 1912, the instrument did not really become popular until the mid-20th century, when it was "discovered" by classical accordionists.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] He said they heard shows with "Frosini, Deiro repertoire or folkloristic music." However, he found it was not possible to get a good education on accordion, as accordionists were not accepted at major music schools.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The best soloists could hope for was playing at nightclubs on weekends.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Composer Ole Schmidt liked the instrument and in 1958 he composed a *Symphonic Fantasy and Allegro, op.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In Europe, free bass accordion performance has reached a very high level and the instrument is considered worthy of serious study in music conservatories.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The Italian composer Salvatore Sciarrino (b.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] It was well received by most European audiences and was released on a compilation disc of Sciarrino's other works on the Winter and Winter label.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Young generation composers who have written for accordion include Christina Athinodorou (b.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] 1981) who wrote "Virgules" for Solo Accordion (2009) featuring the combined use between the stradella bass and the chromatic button system.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In the United States, the free-bass accordion is heard occasionally.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Beginning in the 1960s, competitive performance on the accordion of classical piano compositions, by the great masters of music, occurred.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Although never mainstreamed in the larger musical scene, this convergence with traditional classical music propelled young accordionists to an ultimate involvement with classical music heretofore not experienced.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] A number of American instrumentalists did succeed in demonstrating the unique orchestral capabilities of the free bass accordion while performing at the nation's premier concert venues.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In the process they encouraged contemporary composers to write for the instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Included among the leading orchestral artists was John Serry, Sr.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] A concert accordionist, soloist, composer, and arranger, Serry performed extensively in both symphonic orchestras and jazz ensembles as well as on live radio and television broadcasts.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] His refined poetic artistry gained respect for the free bass accordion as a serious concert instrument among prominent classical musicians and conductors of the early 20th century.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In addition, his *Concerto For Free Bass Accordion* was completed in 1966 and illustrates the vast orchestral potentialities of the instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Recently Guy Klucevsek has built a reputation on combining folk styles with classical forms and makes extensive use of the free bass.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] New York's William Schimmel, who composes and performs in many genres, is a leading exponent of the "quint" style free bass system and uses it extensively in tandem with the standard stradella system.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Nick Ariondo, Los Angeles based accordionist/composer, has created a large repertoire for both free bass and standard stradella systems, performing throughout his career with vocalists, in solo recitals, chamber music settings and with orchestra.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Opposite the Titano Accordion "quint" free bass system designed by Willard Palmer, Ariondo and the late Tommy Gumina are two artists in the United States that play a reverse "quint" free bass system (no converter, only free bass).
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Ariondo's "Perpetual Motion" (Paganini) video demonstrates the artistic capabilities of the free bass accordion .
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In Canada several performers also contributed extensively to the acceptance of the Free Bass Accordion as a respected member of orchestral ensembles throughout North America.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Among the leading performers, educators and composers is Joseph Macerollo who has achieved widespread acclaim as an interpreter of both contemporary and classical compositions for the instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Other notable classical accordion performers include Pauline Oliveros, Owen Murray and Rob Reich of the Tin Hat Trio.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In the early twentieth century the Hohner corporation also assumed an important role in the evolution of the accordion from a folk instrument which was primarily performed by ear into a "legitimate" orchestral instrument which could be accepted on the concert hall stage.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In the early 1900s this German manufacturer of musical instruments formed an accordion orchestra consisting entirely of thirty musicians who successfully toured throughout the nation while performing classical music.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In addition, an accordion college was established in order to facilitate the development of professional educators who specialized in the performance of the instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Ironically, the founding of The Hohner Symphony Accordion Orchestra in Trossingen, Germany in 1931 was somewhat problematic since it also coincided with the emergence of the Nazi party prior to World War II.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Concert performances on the accordion remained popular with the German public however and Germany's soldiers even embraced the instrument on the battlefield.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Further attempts by Nazi government officials to ban the instrument entirely were subsequently never enforced after the Hohner company argued that the accordion was in fact a "legitimate" German folk instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] The accordion orchestra was resurrected within the framework of an even larger ensemble within the United States in the post World War II era during the 1940s.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] Unlike its smaller cousin the accordion band, this iteration of a purely free-reed symphonic ensemble typically utilized between fifty and one hundred musicians who specialized in the performance of classical and popular musical selections as opposed to a lighter musical repertoire.
[src:accordion/accordion-music-genres] In the United States, such symphonic accordion orchestras often performed under the baton of prominent soloists including Jacob C.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] A **reed rank** inside an accordion is a single full set of the reeds that are the means to achieve the instrument's sound range.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] These reed ranks are located in the **reed chamber**.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Most accordions to this date typically have between two and four reed ranks on the treble side and between three and five reed ranks on the bass side.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] These can usually be selected individually or combined in various ways to provide a range of different timbres, by use of **register switches** arranged by register from high to low.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] More of the top-line expensive accordions may contain five or six reed blocks on the treble side for different tunings, typically found in accordions that stress musette sounds.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] How many reeds an accordion has is specified by the number of treble ranks and bass ranks.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] For example, a 4/5 accordion has four reeds on the treble side and five on the bass side.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] A 3/4 accordion has three reeds on the treble sides and four on the bass side.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Reed ranks are classified by either organ 'foot-length' stops or instrument names.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Visually, they each have a fixed dot in a three-level icon as displayed in the photo on the right and tables below.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] These icons display when more than one reed-rank is in use.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] The pitch of a single bank of reeds is traditionally defined in a similar manner to the organ stops of a pipe organ.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] A bank that sounds at unison pitch when keys are depressed is called 8′ (pronounced "eight-foot") pitch: alluding to the length of the lowest-sounding organ pipe in that rank, which is approximately eight feet.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] For the same reason, a stop that sounds an octave higher is at 4′ pitch, and one that sounds an octave lower than unison pitch is at 16′ pitch.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Most reed registers are normally in relative octave tuning, but rarely, some instruments have a reed bank tuned to a perfect fifth relative to the 8′ stop (or some octave of that) such as the Bayan (accordion) in the new models.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] This is a similar arrangement to stops for a pipe organ.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] On accordions with two 8′ ranks, one is tuned a fraction of a semitone (usually no more than 25 cents) higher than the other ranks.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] This causes beats when the two 8′ ranks sound together, creating a distinctive tremolo timbre.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Tunings where the difference between the two is small and the beats are less noticeable are referred to as "dry", whereas those where the difference is large are referred to as "wet".
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Accordions with three 8′ ranks have the third tuned the same distance below the center, doubling the effect of the beats when all three play.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Here are a few examples of right-hand manual switches on a typical large accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Instead of automatic switches, some accordions have individual switches for the reed ranks that can be used in any combination, like organ stops.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] In addition to the master switch located with the other switches shown above, professional-grade accordions often have at least one extra master switch: either a *chin master* at the top of the instrument or *palm master* switch located at the side of the keyboard.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] These allow for faster changes to the register while the right hand is playing the melody.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Some have double bassoon (16′ + 16′), equivalent to a tenor violin, and the tenor musette (16′ + 16′ + 8′) is also found in some model accordions.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] High-end accordions often have a feature called a *cassotto* (Italian for "box"), also referred to as a "tone chamber", in the treble (right-hand) reed section.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] In this design, certain reed sets (usually one set of middle reeds, and the set of low reeds) are mounted at a 90° angle to the remaining reeds.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] The sound from these specially-mounted reeds must then travel farther, and along a different path, before leaving the instrument, muting its harmonics (*partials*) and creating a distinctively mellow, refined sound.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] The sound of cassotto bassoon (low) reeds is particularly favored by jazz accordionists.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] The cassotto design requires a sophisticated treble mechanism where each key must open and close air passages not only for reeds mounted at the traditional angle, but also for air passages at a relative 90° angle (for the cassotto reeds).
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] To do this properly, each rod and pad must be positioned precisely in relation to its perpendicular counterpart.
[src:accordion/accordion-reed-ranks-and-switches] Because of the considerable extra time required for the cassotto's construction and adjustment, cassotto accordions cost considerably more than similar non-cassotto models.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion belongs to the free-reed aerophone family.
[src:accordion/accordion] Other instruments in this family include the concertina, harmonica, and bandoneon.
[src:accordion/accordion] The concertina and bandoneon do not have the melody–accompaniment duality.
[src:accordion/accordion] The harmoneon is also related and, while having the descant vs. melody dualism, tries to make it less pronounced.
[src:accordion/accordion] The harmonium and American reed organ are in the same family, but are typically larger than an accordion and sit on a surface or the floor.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion is played by compressing or expanding the bellows while pressing buttons or keys, causing *pallets* to open, which allow air to flow across strips of brass or steel, called *reeds*.
[src:accordion/accordion] These vibrate to produce sound inside the body.
[src:accordion/accordion] Valves on opposing reeds of each note are used to make the instrument's reeds sound louder without air leaking from each reed block.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion is widely spread across the world because of the waves of migration from Europe to the Americas and other regions.
[src:accordion/accordion] In Europe and North America, some popular music acts also make use of the instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion] Additionally, the accordion is used in cajun, zydeco, jazz, and klezmer music, and in both solo and orchestral performances of classical music.
[src:accordion/accordion] Many conservatories in Europe have classical accordion departments.
[src:accordion/accordion] The oldest name for this group of instruments is *harmonika*, from the Ancient Greek: ἁρμονικός *harmonikós* meaning "harmonic, musical".
[src:accordion/accordion] Today, native versions of the name *accordion* are more common.
[src:accordion/accordion] These names refer to the type of accordion patented by Cyrill Demian, which concerned "automatically coupled chords on the bass side".
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion's basic form is believed to have been invented in Berlin, in 1822, by Christian Friedrich Ludwig Buschmann, although one instrument was discovered in 2006 that appears to have been built earlier.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion is one of several European inventions of the early 19th century that use free reeds driven by a bellows.
[src:accordion/accordion] An instrument called *accordion* was first patented in 1829 by Cyrill Demian in Vienna.
[src:accordion/accordion] Cyrill Demian's instrument bore little resemblance to modern instruments.
[src:accordion/accordion] It only had a left-hand buttonboard, with the right hand simply operating the bellows.
[src:accordion/accordion] One key feature for which Demian sought the patent was the sounding of an entire chord by depressing one key.
[src:accordion/accordion] His instrument could also sound two chords with the same key, one for each bellow direction (a *bisonoric* action).
[src:accordion/accordion] At that time in Vienna, mouth harmonicas with *Kanzellen* (chambers) had already been available for many years, along with bigger instruments driven by hand bellows.
[src:accordion/accordion] The diatonic key arrangement was also already used on mouth-blown instruments.
[src:accordion/accordion] Demian's patent thus covered an accompanying instrument: an accordion played with the left hand, opposite to how contemporary chromatic hand harmonicas were played, small and light enough for travelers to take with them and used to accompany singing.
[src:accordion/accordion] The patent also described instruments with both bass and treble sections, although Demian preferred the bass-only instrument owing to its cost and weight advantages.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion was introduced from Germany into Britain in about the year 1828.
[src:accordion/accordion] The instrument was noted in *The Times* in 1831 as one new to British audiences and was not favourably reviewed, but nevertheless it soon became popular.
[src:accordion/accordion] It had also become popular with New Yorkers by the mid-1840s.
[src:accordion/accordion] The earliest history of the accordion in Russia is poorly documented.
[src:accordion/accordion] Nevertheless, according to Russian researchers, the earliest known simple accordions were made in Tula, Russia, by Ivan Sizov and Timofey Vorontsov around 1830, after they received an early accordion from Germany.
[src:accordion/accordion] By the late 1840s, the instrument was already very widespread.
[src:accordion/accordion] Together the factories of the two masters were producing 10,000 instruments a year.
[src:accordion/accordion] By 1866, over 50,000 instruments were being produced yearly by Tula and neighbouring villages, and by 1874 the yearly production was over 700,000.
[src:accordion/accordion] By the 1860s, Novgorod, Vyatka and Saratov governorates also had significant accordion production.
[src:accordion/accordion] By the 1880s, the list included Oryol, Ryazan, Moscow, Tver, Vologda, Kostroma, Nizhny Novgorod and Simbirsk, and many of these places created their own varieties of the instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion] After Demian's invention, other accordions appeared, some featuring only the right-handed keyboard for playing melodies.
[src:accordion/accordion] It took English inventor Charles Wheatstone to bring both chords and keyboard together in one squeezebox.
[src:accordion/accordion] His 1844 patent for what he called a *concertina* also featured the ability to easily tune the reeds from the outside with a simple tool.
[src:accordion/accordion] The Austrian musician Adolf Müller described a great variety of instruments in his 1854 book **Schule für Accordion**.
[src:accordion/accordion] At the time, Vienna and London had a close musical relationship, with musicians often performing in both cities in the same year, so it is possible that Wheatstone was aware of this type of instrument and may have used them to put his key-arrangement ideas into practice.
[src:accordion/accordion] Jeune's *flutina* resembles Wheatstone's concertina in internal construction and tone colour, but it appears to complement Demian's accordion functionally.
[src:accordion/accordion] The flutina is a one-sided bisonoric melody-only instrument whose keys are operated with the right hand while the bellows are operated with the left.
[src:accordion/accordion] When the two instruments are combined, the result is quite similar to diatonic button accordions still manufactured today.
[src:accordion/accordion] Further innovations followed and continue to the present.
[src:accordion/accordion] Modern accordions may incorporate electronics such as condenser microphones and tone and volume controls so that the accordion can be plugged into a PA system or keyboard amplifier for live shows.
[src:accordion/accordion] Some 2010s-era accordions may incorporate MIDI sensors and circuitry, enabling the accordion to be plugged into a synth module and produce accordion sounds or other synthesized instrument sounds, such as piano or organ.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordions have many configurations and types.
[src:accordion/accordion] What may be easy to do with one type of accordion could be technically challenging or impossible with another, and proficiency with one layout may not translate to another.
[src:accordion/accordion] The most obvious difference between accordions is their right-hand sides.
[src:accordion/accordion] Piano accordions use a piano-style musical keyboard; button accordions use a buttonboard.
[src:accordion/accordion] Button accordions are furthermore differentiated by their usage of a chromatic or diatonic buttonboard for the right-hand side.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordions may be either bisonoric, producing different pitches depending on the direction of bellows movement, or unisonoric, producing the same pitch in both directions.
[src:accordion/accordion] Chromatic button accordions also tend to be unisonoric, while diatonic button accordions tend to be bisonoric, though notable exceptions exist.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordion size is not standardized, and may vary significantly from model to model.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordions vary not only in their dimensions and weight, but also in the number of buttons or keys present in the right- and left-hand keyboards.
[src:accordion/accordion] For example, piano accordions may have as few as 8 bass buttons (two rows of four), or up to 140 (seven rows of twenty) or beyond.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordions also vary by their available registers and by their specific tuning and voicing.
[src:accordion/accordion] Despite these differences, all accordions share several common components.
[src:accordion/accordion] The bellows is the most recognizable part of the instrument, and the primary means of articulation.
[src:accordion/accordion] The production of sound in an accordion is in direct proportion to the motion of the bellows by the player.
[src:accordion/accordion] In a sense, the role of the bellows can be compared to the role of moving a violin's bow on bowed strings.
[src:accordion/accordion] For a more direct analogy, the bellows can be compared to the role of breathing for a singer.
[src:accordion/accordion] The bellows is located between the right- and left-hand keyboards, and is made from pleated layers of cloth and cardboard, with added leather and metal.
[src:accordion/accordion] It is used to create pressure and vacuum, driving air across the internal reeds and producing sound by their vibrations, applied pressure increases the volume.
[src:accordion/accordion] The keyboard touch is not expressive and does not affect dynamics: all expression is effected through the bellows.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion's body consists of two boxes, commonly made of wood, joined by the bellows.
[src:accordion/accordion] These boxes house reed chambers for the right- and left-hand keyboards.
[src:accordion/accordion] Each side has grilles in order to facilitate the transmission of air in and out of the instrument and to allow the sound to project.
[src:accordion/accordion] The grille at the right-hand side is usually larger and is often shaped for decorative purposes.
[src:accordion/accordion] The right-hand keyboard is normally used for playing the melody and the left-hand one for playing the accompaniment; however, skilled players can reverse these roles and play melodies with the left hand.
[src:accordion/accordion] The term *accordion* covers a wide range of instruments, with varying components.
[src:accordion/accordion] All instruments have reed ranks of some format, apart from reedless digital accordions.
[src:accordion/accordion] Not all have switches to change registers or ranks, as some have only one treble register and one bass register.
[src:accordion/accordion] The most typical accordion is the piano accordion, which is used for many musical genres.
[src:accordion/accordion] Another type of accordion is the button accordion, which is used in musical traditions including Cajun, Conjunto and Tejano music, Swiss and Slovenian-Austro-German Alpine music, and Argentinian tango music.
[src:accordion/accordion] The Helikon-style accordion has multiple flared horns projecting out of the left side to strengthen the bass tone.
[src:accordion/accordion] The word "Helikon" refers to a deep-pitched tuba.
[src:accordion/accordion] Different systems exist for the right-hand keyboard of an accordion, which is normally used for playing the melody (while it can also play chords).
[src:accordion/accordion] Some use a button layout arranged in one way or another, while others use a piano-style keyboard.
[src:accordion/accordion] Each system has different claimed benefits by those who prefer it.
[src:accordion/accordion] Different systems are also in use for the left-hand keyboard, which is normally used for playing the accompaniment.
[src:accordion/accordion] These usually use distinct bass buttons and often have buttons with concavities or studs to help the player navigate the layout despite not being able to see the buttons while playing.
[src:accordion/accordion] Inside the accordion are the reeds that generate the instrument tones.
[src:accordion/accordion] These are organized in different sounding *banks*, which can be further combined into *registers* producing differing *timbres*.
[src:accordion/accordion] All but the smaller accordions are equipped with switches that control which combination of reed banks operate, organized from high to low registers.
[src:accordion/accordion] Each register stop produces a separate sound timbre, many of which also differ in octaves or in how different octaves are combined.
[src:accordion/accordion] See the accordion reed ranks and switches article for further explanation and audio samples.
[src:accordion/accordion] All but the smaller accordions usually have treble switches.
[src:accordion/accordion] The larger and more expensive accordions often also have bass switches to give options for the reed bank on the bass side.
[src:accordion/accordion] In describing or pricing an accordion, the first factor is size, expressed in number of keys on either side.
[src:accordion/accordion] For a piano type, this could for one example be 37/96, meaning 37 treble keys (three octaves plus one note) on the treble side and 96 bass keys.
[src:accordion/accordion] A second aspect of size is the width of the white keys, which means that even accordions with the same number of keys have keyboards of different lengths, ranging from 14 inches (36 cm) for a child's accordion to 19 inches (48 cm) for an adult-sized instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion] After size, the price and weight of an accordion is largely dependent on the number of reed ranks on either side, either on a cassotto or not, and to a lesser degree on the number of combinations available through register switches.
[src:accordion/accordion] The next, but important, factor is the quality of the reeds, the highest grade called "a mano" (meaning "hand-made"), the next "tipo a mano" ("like hand-made"), lower grades including "export" and several more.
[src:accordion/accordion] Price is also affected by the use of costly woods, luxury decorations, and features such as a palm switch, grille mute, and so on.
[src:accordion/accordion] Some accordion makers sell a range of different models, from a less-expensive base model to a more costly luxury model.
[src:accordion/accordion] Another factor affecting the price is the presence of electronics, such as condenser microphones, volume and tone controls, or MIDI sensors and connections.
[src:accordion/accordion] The larger piano and chromatic button accordions are usually heavier than other smaller squeezeboxes, and are equipped with two shoulder straps to make it easier to balance the weight and increase bellows control while sitting, and avoid dropping the instrument while standing.
[src:accordion/accordion] Other accordions, such as the diatonic button accordion, have only a single shoulder strap and a right hand thumb strap.
[src:accordion/accordion] All accordions have a (mostly adjustable) leather strap on the left-hand side to keep the player's hand in position while drawing the bellows.
[src:accordion/accordion] There are also straps above and below the bellows to keep it securely closed when the instrument is not being played.
[src:accordion/accordion] In the 2010s, a range of electronic and digital accordions were introduced.
[src:accordion/accordion] They have an electronic sound module which creates the accordion sound, and most use MIDI systems to encode the keypresses and transmit them to the sound module.
[src:accordion/accordion] A digital accordion can have hundreds of sounds, which can include different types of accordions and even non-accordion sounds, such as pipe organ, piano, or guitar.
[src:accordion/accordion] Sensors are used on the buttons and keys, such as magnetic reed switches.
[src:accordion/accordion] Sensors are also used on the bellows to transmit the pushing and pulling of the bellows to the sound module.
[src:accordion/accordion] Digital accordions may have features not found in acoustic instruments, such as a piano-style sustain pedal, a modulation control for changing keys, and a portamento effect.
[src:accordion/accordion] As an electronic instrument, these types of accordions are plugged into a PA system or keyboard amplifier to produce sound.
[src:accordion/accordion] Some digital accordions have a small internal speaker and amplifier, so they can be used without a PA system or keyboard amplifier, at least for practicing and small venues like coffeehouses.
[src:accordion/accordion] One benefit of electronic accordions is that they can be practiced with headphones, making them inaudible to other people nearby.
[src:accordion/accordion] On a digital accordion, the volume of the right-hand keyboard and the left-hand buttons can be independently adjusted.
[src:accordion/accordion] Acoustic-digital hybrid accordions also exist.
[src:accordion/accordion] They are acoustic accordions (with reeds, bellows, and so on), but they also contain sensors, electronics, and MIDI connections, which provides a wider range of sound options.
[src:accordion/accordion] An acoustic-digital hybrid may be manufactured in this form, or it may be an acoustic accordion which has had aftermarket electronics sensors and connections added.
[src:accordion/accordion] Several companies sell aftermarket electronics kits, but they are typically installed by professional accordion technicians, because of the complex and delicate nature of the internal parts of an accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] Various hybrid accordions have been created between instruments of different buttonboards and actions.
[src:accordion/accordion] The most expensive accordions are typically fully hand-made, particularly the reeds; completely hand-made reeds have a better tonal quality than even the best automatically manufactured ones.
[src:accordion/accordion] Some accordions have been modified by individuals striving to bring a more pure sound out of low-end instruments, such as the ones improved by Yutaka Usui, a Japanese craftsman.
[src:accordion/accordion] The manufacture of an accordion is only a partly automated process.
[src:accordion/accordion] In a sense, all accordions are handmade, since there is always some hand assembly of the small parts required.
[src:accordion/accordion] The general process involves making the individual parts, assembling the subsections, assembling the entire instrument, and final decorating and packaging.
[src:accordion/accordion] Notable centres of production are the Italian cities of Stradella and Castelfidardo, with many small and medium size manufacturers especially at the latter.
[src:accordion/accordion] Castelfidardo honours the memory of Paolo Soprani who was one of the first large-scale producers.
[src:accordion/accordion] Maugein Freres has built accordions in the French town of Tulle since 1919, and the company is now the last complete-process manufacturer of accordions in France.
[src:accordion/accordion] German companies such as Hohner and Weltmeister made large numbers of accordions, but production diminished by the end of the 20th century.
[src:accordion/accordion] Hohner still manufactures its top-end models in Germany, and *Weltmeister* instruments are still handmade by HARMONA Akkordeon GmbH in Klingenthal.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion has traditionally been used to perform folk or ethnic music, popular music, and transcriptions from the operatic and light-classical music repertoire.
[src:accordion/accordion] It was also used by the Kikuyu tribe in Kenya and is the main instrument in the traditional Mwomboko dance.
[src:accordion/accordion] Today the instrument is sometimes heard in contemporary pop styles, such as rock and pop-rock, and occasionally even in serious classical music concerts, as well as advertisements.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion's popularity spread rapidly: it has mostly been associated with the common people, and was propagated by Europeans who emigrated around the world.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion in both button and piano forms became a favorite of folk musicians and has been integrated into traditional music styles all over the world: see the list of music styles that incorporate the accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] Early jazz accordionists include Charles Melrose, who recorded *Wailing Blues/Barrel House Stomp* (1930, Voc.
[src:accordion/accordion] 1503) with the Cellar Boys; Buster Moten, who played second piano and accordion in the Bennie Moten orchestra; and Jack Cornell, who did recordings with Irving Mills.
[src:accordion/accordion] Later jazz accordionists from the United States include Steve Bach, Milton DeLugg, Orlando DiGirolamo, Angelo Di Pippo, Dominic Frontiere, Guy Klucevsek, Yuri Lemeshev, Frank Marocco, Dr.
[src:accordion/accordion] William Schimmel, John Serry Sr., Lee Tomboulian, and Art Van Damme.
[src:accordion/accordion] French jazz accordionists include Richard Galliano, Bernard Lubat, and Vincent Peirani.
[src:accordion/accordion] Norwegian jazz accordionists include Asmund Bjørken, Stian Carstensen, Gabriel Fliflet, Frode Haltli, and Eivin One Pedersen.
[src:accordion/accordion] The constraints of the Stradella bass system, limiting the left hand to preset chord buttons, is a barrier to some jazz chord conventions.
[src:accordion/accordion] Jazz accordionists expand the range of chord possibilities by using more than one chord button simultaneously, or by using combinations of a chord button and a bass note other than the typical root of the chord.
[src:accordion/accordion] An example of the former technique is used to play a minor seventh chord.
[src:accordion/accordion] To play an Am7(add9) chord, the Am and Em preset buttons are pressed simultaneously, along with an A bassnote.
[src:accordion/accordion] An example of the latter technique is used to play the half-diminished chord.
[src:accordion/accordion] To play an Eø7, a Gm preset button is pressed along with an E bassnote.
[src:accordion/accordion] For the left hand, the free-bass system is used in jazz as a means of creating complex chord voicings.
[src:accordion/accordion] Jazz harmony that would otherwise be difficult to replicate with the Stradella bass system, such as tritone substitutions, become more accessible using a free-bass accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion appeared in popular music from the 1900s to the 1960s.
[src:accordion/accordion] This half-century is often called the "golden age of the accordion".
[src:accordion/accordion] Five players, Pietro Frosini, the two brothers Count Guido Deiro and Pietro Deiro and Slovenian brothers Vilko Ovsenik and Slavko Avsenik, Charles Magnante were major influences at this time.
[src:accordion/accordion] Most vaudeville theaters closed during the Great Depression, but accordionists during the 1930s–1950s taught and performed for radio.
[src:accordion/accordion] Included among this group was the concert virtuoso John Serry, Sr.
[src:accordion/accordion] During the 1950s through the 1980s the accordion received significant exposure on television with performances by Myron Floren on *The Lawrence Welk Show*.
[src:accordion/accordion] In the late 1950s and early 1960s, the accordion declined in popularity because of the rise of rock and roll.
[src:accordion/accordion] The first accordionist to appear and perform at the Newport Jazz Festival was Angelo DiPippo.
[src:accordion/accordion] He can be seen playing his accordion in the motion picture *The Godfather*.
[src:accordion/accordion] He also composed and performed with his accordion on part of the soundtrack of Woody Allen's movie *To Rome With Love*.
[src:accordion/accordion] He was featured twice on *The Tonight Show* with Johnny Carson.
[src:accordion/accordion] Richard Galliano is an internationally known accordionist whose repertoire covers jazz, tango nuevo, Latin, and classical.
[src:accordion/accordion] Some popular bands use the instrument to create distinctive sounds.
[src:accordion/accordion] Grammy Award-winning parodist "Weird Al" Yankovic plays the accordion on many of his musical tracks, particularly his polkas.
[src:accordion/accordion] Yankovic was trained in the accordion as a child.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion has also been used in the rock genre, most notably by John Linnell of They Might Be Giants, featuring more prominently in the band's earlier works.
[src:accordion/accordion] The instrument is still frequently used during live performances, and continues to make appearances in their studio albums.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordion is also used in the music of the Dropkick Murphys and Gogol Bordello.
[src:accordion/accordion] Tom Waits used the accordion extensively (often played by Dr.
[src:accordion/accordion] William Schimmel) on his album *Rain Dogs* and *Franks Wild Years*.
[src:accordion/accordion] The folk metal subgenre also employs accordionists, but they are otherwise generally rare in other genres.
[src:accordion/accordion] Full-time accordionists in folk metal seem even rarer, but they are still utilized for studio work, as flexible keyboardists are usually more accessible for live performances.
[src:accordion/accordion] The Finnish symphonic folk-metal band Turisas used to have a full-time accordionist, employing classical and polka sensibilities alongside a violinist.
[src:accordion/accordion] One of their accordionists, Netta Skog, is now a member of Ensiferum, another folk-metal band.
[src:accordion/accordion] Another Finnish metal band, Korpiklaani, invokes a type of Finnish polka called humppa, and also has a full-time accordionist.
[src:accordion/accordion] Sarah Kiener, the former hurdy-gurdy player for the Swiss melodic-death-folk metal band Eluveitie, played a Helvetic accordion known as a *zugerörgeli*.
[src:accordion/accordion] Although best known as a folk instrument, it has grown in popularity among classical composers.
[src:accordion/accordion] The earliest surviving concert piece is **Thême varié très brillant pour accordéon methode Reisner**, written in 1836 by Louise Reisner of Paris.
[src:accordion/accordion] Other composers, including the Russian Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky, the Italian Umberto Giordano, and the American Charles Ives, wrote works for the diatonic button accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] The first composer to write specifically for the chromatic accordion was Paul Hindemith.
[src:accordion/accordion] In 1922, the Austrian Alban Berg included an accordion in *Wozzeck*, Op.
[src:accordion/accordion] In 1937, the first accordion concerto was composed in Russia.
[src:accordion/accordion] Other notable composers have written for the accordion during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:accordion/accordion] Included among this group was the Italian-American John Serry Sr., whose *Concerto for Free Bass Accordion* was completed in 1964.
[src:accordion/accordion] In addition, the American accordionist Robert Davine composed his *Divertimento for Flute, Clarinet, Bassoon and Accordion* as a work for chamber orchestra.
[src:accordion/accordion] The American Accordionists' Association awarded a commission to Nicolas Flagello in 1964 for his virtuosic *Introduction and Scherzo* for solo accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] Perry featured the accordion in his orchestral suite *Six Title Themes in Search of a Movie* (2008).
[src:accordion/accordion] The experimental composer Howard Skempton began his musical career as an accordionist, and has written numerous solo works for it.
[src:accordion/accordion] In his work *Drang* (1999), British composer John Palmer pushed the expressive possibilities of the accordion/bayan.
[src:accordion/accordion] Luciano Berio wrote *Sequenza XIII* (1995) for accordionist Teodoro Anzellotti.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordionists like Mogens Ellegaard, Joseph Macerollo, Nick Ariondo, Friedrich Lips, Hugo Noth, Dr.
[src:accordion/accordion] William Schimmel (also a composer), Stefan Hussong, Teodoro Anzellotti, and Geir Draugsvoll, encouraged composers to write new music for the accordion (solo and chamber music) and also started playing baroque music on the free bass accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] French composer Henri Dutilleux used an accordion in both his late song cycles *Correspondences* (2003) and *Le Temps L'Horloge* (2009).
[src:accordion/accordion] Russian-born composer Sofia Gubaidulina has composed solos, concertos, and chamber works for accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] Astor Piazzolla's concert tangos are performed widely.
[src:accordion/accordion] Piazzolla performed on the bandoneon, but his works are also performed on or accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] William schimmel and "The Tango Project" recorded a number of hit recordings and appeared in the movie *Scent of a Woman* with Al Pacino which earned Pacino an Oscar.
[src:accordion/accordion] Their recordings were used in many films.
[src:accordion/accordion] The earliest mention of the novel accordion instrument in Australian music occurs in the 1830s.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion initially competed against cheaper and more convenient reed instruments such as mouth organ, concertina and melodeon.
[src:accordion/accordion] Frank Fracchia was an Australian accordion composer and copies of his works "My dear, can you come out tonight" and "Dancing with you" are preserved in Australian libraries.
[src:accordion/accordion] Other Australian composers who arranged music for accordion include Reginald Stoneham.
[src:accordion/accordion] The popularity of the accordion peaked in the late 1930s and continued until the 1950s.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion was particularly favoured by buskers.
[src:accordion/accordion] The Accordion Society of Australia (ASA) holds state based and national accordion competitions throughout Australia.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion is a traditional instrument in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:accordion/accordion] It is the dominant instrument used in sevdalinka, a traditional genre of folk music from Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion was brought to Brazil by settlers and immigrants from Europe, especially from Italy and Germany, who mainly settled in the south (Rio Grande do Sul, Santa Catarina and Paraná).
[src:accordion/accordion] The first instrument brought was a "Concertina" (a 120 button chromatic accordion).
[src:accordion/accordion] The instrument was popular in the 1950s, and it was common to find several accordions in the same house.
[src:accordion/accordion] There are many different configurations and tunes which were adapted from the cultures that came from Europe.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordion is the official symbol instrument of the Rio Grande do Sul state, where it was voted by unanimity in the deputy chamber.
[src:accordion/accordion] During the boom of accordions there were around 65 factories in Brazil, where most of them (52) in the south, in Rio Grande do Sul state, with only 7 outside the south.
[src:accordion/accordion] One of the most famous and genuinely Brazilian brands was Accordeões Todeschini from Bento Gonçalves-RS, closed in 1973.
[src:accordion/accordion] The Todeschini accordion is very appreciated today and survives with very few maintainers.
[src:accordion/accordion] The most notable musicians of button accordions are Renato Borghetti, Adelar Bertussi, Albino Manique and Edson Dutra.
[src:accordion/accordion] Compared to many other countries, the instrument is very popular in mainstream pop music.
[src:accordion/accordion] In some parts of the country, such as the northeast it is the most popular melodic instrument.
[src:accordion/accordion] As opposed to most European folk accordions, a very dry tuning is usually used in Brazil.
[src:accordion/accordion] In this musical style the typical combination is a trio of accordion, triangle and zabumba (a type of drum).
[src:accordion/accordion] This style has gained popularity recently, in particular among the student population of the southeast of the country (in the Forró Universitário genre, with important exponents today being Falamansa, and trios such as Trio Dona Zefa, Trio Virgulino and Trio Alvorada).
[src:accordion/accordion] Moreover, the accordion is the principal instrument in Junina music (music of the São João Festival), with Mario Zan having been a very important exponent of this music.
[src:accordion/accordion] It is an important instrument in Sertanejo (and Caipira) music, which originated in the midwest and southeast of Brazil, and subsequently has gained popularity throughout the country.
[src:accordion/accordion] The number of accordionists in China exceeds every other country in the world, and possibly every country combined.
[src:accordion/accordion] Introduced in 1926, the accordion has risen to popularity in China throughout the years, thanks to Russian teachers and its being a popular instrument in the People's Liberation Army, and remains popular.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion is also a traditional instrument in Colombia, commonly associated with the vallenato and cumbia genres.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion has been used by tropipop musicians such as Carlos Vives, Andrés Cabas, Fonseca (singer) and Bacilos, as well as rock musicians such as Juanes and pop musicians as Shakira.
[src:accordion/accordion] Vallenato, who emerged in the early twentieth century in Valledupar, and have come to symbolize the folk music of Colombia.
[src:accordion/accordion] Every year in April, Colombia holds one of the most important musical festivals in the country: the Vallenato Legend Festival.
[src:accordion/accordion] The festival holds contests for best accordion player.
[src:accordion/accordion] Once every decade, the "King of Kings" accordion competition takes place, where winners of the previous festivals compete for the highest possible award for a vallenato accordion player: the *Pilonera Mayor* prize.
[src:accordion/accordion] This is the world's largest competitive accordion festival.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordion is often played at traditional Czech pubs, such as U Flekú, Prague.
[src:accordion/accordion] In 18XX, the accordion was brought to Japan.
[src:accordion/accordion] The accordion is an important instrument to *ronggeng* performed among the Malay and Peranakan; it is also often interchangeable with the harmonium in playing the ghazal; Suhaimi Mohd Zain was one notable accordionist who frequently collaborated with folk pop singer Siti Nurhaliza.
[src:accordion/accordion] Norteño heavily relies on the accordion; it is a genre related to polka.
[src:accordion/accordion] Ramón Ayala, known in Mexico as the "King of the Accordion", is a norteño musician.
[src:accordion/accordion] Cumbia, which features the accordion, is also popular with musicians such as Celso Piña, creating a more contemporary style.
[src:accordion/accordion] U.S.-born Mexican musician Julieta Venegas incorporates the sound of the instrument into rock, pop and folk.
[src:accordion/accordion] She was influenced by her fellow Chicanos Los Lobos who also use the music of the accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] According to Barbara Demick in *Nothing to Envy*, the accordion is known as "the people's instrument" and all North Korean teachers were expected to learn the accordion.
[src:accordion/accordion] Accordions are played in Tejano music, Cajun and Creole music, zydeco, klezmer, and polka.
[src:accordion/accordion] Included among the leading accordion orchestras were: The New York Accordion Symphony in New York City, The Springfield Accordion Orchestra in Massachusetts, The Houston Accordion Symphony in Houston, Texas and The Philadelphia Accordion Orchestra in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:accordion/accordion] By the 1960s recordings such *Pietro Deiro Presents the Accordion Orchestra* also emerged on leading record labels in the United States and were even praised for their high level of musicality in *The Billboard* magazine.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The **piano action mechanism** (also known as the **key action mechanism** or simply the **action**) of a piano or other musical keyboard is the mechanical assembly which translates the depression of the keys into rapid motion of a hammer, which creates sound by striking the strings.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Action can refer to that of a piano or other musical keyboards, including the electronic or digital stage piano and synthesizer, on which some models have "weighted keys", which simulate the touch and feel of an acoustic piano.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The design of the key action mechanism determines the "weight" of the keys, i.e., the force required to sound a note or striking power.
[src:accordion/action-piano] "A professional pianist is likely to care most about the piano's action, because that is what controls its responsiveness and relative lightness--or heaviness--of touch.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Roughly speaking, a piano's action is light when its keys fall easily under the fingers, and heavy when a noticeable downward thrust is required.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The string hammer action was the important innovation that Bartolomeo Cristofori created when he invented the pianoforte; Cristofori is credited with building his first instrument by 1700.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Although similar hammer actions were devised at about the same time by Marius (1716) and Christoph Gottlieb Schröter (1717), Cristofori was the only one of these three to actually construct an instrument.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Alfred Dolge notes the first pianos were quite similar in construction to contemporary harpsichords, while incorporating key features of the clavichord, including the soundboard, metal strings, and percussive-string method of creating sounds.
[src:accordion/action-piano] With the piano, a hammer strikes the string, whereas with a harpsichord, a mechanism plucks the string.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Cristofori's improved escapement action (1720) embodied many of the principles still found in 2000-era actions.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In Cristofori's improved escapement action (1720), when the key is depressed, the other end of the key-lever raises a horizontal hopper (which Cristofori called the *linguetta mobile*) with a stepped projection; the hopper raises the curved hammer butt.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Because of the stepped projection, the hopper slips off the key just before the hammer strikes the string, providing the escapement action.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Other modern features are apparent in his diagram, including the presence of a back check to facilitate repetition, and using the rising tip of the key-lever to lift the damper.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Cristofori died in 1731 and left no significant pupils; the instruments that were in process were finished by Giovanni Ferrini, who also is credited with building a pianoforte dated to 1730.
[src:accordion/action-piano] However, Gottfried Silbermann built pianos with both Cristofori and Schröter actions.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Two of Silbermann's pupils, Johannes Zumpe and Americus Backers, popularized the Cristofori action as the "English" action after moving to London.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Zumpe introduced the square piano between 1760 and 1765; Alfred James Hipkins called Zumpe's action "rudimentary but efficient".
[src:accordion/action-piano] The pianos built by Backers did not survive, but his action, patented in 1776, was refined by Robert Stodart (1777) and John Broadwood (1780); the resulting "English" action was noted by Hipkins as "the best single escapement action".
[src:accordion/action-piano] Perhaps the best-known English piano action of the nineteenth century is the Brooks action of 1810.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Silbermann also was responsible for popularizing the Schröter or "German" action.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Dolge characterizes Schröter's original action as "a model of innocent simplicity ... a clumsy device [that] made the touch hard and tough"; Silbermann improved the escapement of the original design.
[src:accordion/action-piano] One of Silbermann's pupils, the Augsburg builder Johann Andreas Stein, further refined Schröter's action in the 1770s by reversing the orientation of the hammer, with the hammer head closer to the player.
[src:accordion/action-piano] As described by Hipkins, in the original "Viennese" action, "the blow is caused by the depression of the key raising the hammer-butt until the back of it comes in contact with a rail at the back of the keyboard, the result being to jerk the hammer to the string".
[src:accordion/action-piano] Stein also refined this action by adding an escapement.
[src:accordion/action-piano] It survived in Viennese pianos almost to the end of the 19th century.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In the 19th century, the English action was further modified by French builders, notably in the invention of the repetition lever, which facilitated rapidly repeating notes.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Sébastien Érard invented the double-escapement action which incorporated the repetition lever, patented in 1808 and 1821; Dolge credits Érard with combining the refined touch of the Vienna action with the force and power of the English action.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The 2000s-era grand piano action is a distant descendant of Cristofori's original.
[src:accordion/action-piano] One of the most well-known French piano actions was created by Jean Schwander in 1844 and improved upon by his son-in-law Josef Herrburger; the Schwander action is still used in Bechstein pianos.
[src:accordion/action-piano] At the turn of the century, Schwander-Herrburger merged with Brooks, giving us the Herrburger-Brooks piano action, which was the definitive piano action of the twentieth century.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Throughout the history of the action, piano makers tended to make it heavier and sturdier, in response to the increasing size, weight, and robustness of the instrument, which was itself part of a general demand for a more powerful sound.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Christian Ernst Friederici invented the first upright piano action in 1745, but it was not well-regarded; Hipkins likened it to a Nuremberg clock.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Ignaz Pleyel adopted Wornum's action and it is popularly known as the Pleyel action.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Manufacturers of electronic keyboards, synthesizers, and digital pianos have used various designs to recreate the feel of an acoustic piano.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The simplest electronic keyboards, sometimes known as *synth-action*, use springs to restore each key to its resting position, similar in concept to a computer keyboard, but providing the least realism.
[src:accordion/action-piano] More sophisticated keyboards incorporate weights in the keys but rely on springs for return, making these *semi-weighted* keyboards fast to depress and slower to return.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Keyboards that use moving weights similar to the motion of hammers without relying on springs are called *hammer-action*.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The hammer weights may vary by the note being played, similar to how keys in the bass register of the piano have heavier hammers to sound the thicker strings than those in the treble register; these are known as *progressive hammer-action* keyboards.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Many electronic keyboards use keys that are hinged at the back to minimize keybed depth; some use keys that pivot in the middle or have longer pivot arms with higher-end keybeds, similar to acoustic pianos.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The action primarily serves to mechanically amplify a relatively small (key) movement into a longer, faster (hammer) movement.
[src:accordion/action-piano] As an overview, when a key is depressed, a felt hammer strikes one or more strings, causing them to vibrate.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The vibrations are transmitted to the soundboard, which makes the audible note.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The action also automatically retracts the hammer after it strikes the string(s), preventing it from damping their vibration.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In addition, as long as the key is depressed, the action also lifts a felt damper off the appropriate string(s), sustaining the vibration.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The main difference between grand and upright piano actions is the direction of motion.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In the grand piano, the soundboard is horizontal; the hammer rises and strikes the string(s) from below, and gravity is used to restore the damper and hammer to their resting positions.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In an upright piano, the soundboard is vertical; the hammer strikes the string(s) from the side, and a combination of gravity and springs are used to restore the damper and hammer to their resting positions.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The key feel when playing repeated notes is slightly different on these actions, as a result.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Traditionally, the individual parts of the action of an acoustic piano are made of wood with metal pins and pivots; some manufacturers have switched to using plastic and composite materials for certain items to add strength and environmental stability.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The key (1) is comparable to a seesaw; when the player depresses one end, the end on the other side of the pivot point rises.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The capstan (2) is on the rising side of the key.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The rising capstan lifts the wippen (3), which is connected to the L-shaped jack (5).
[src:accordion/action-piano] The rising wippen carries the long end of the jack, which pushes on a felt knuckle near the pivot point of the hammer shank (8), causing the felt-covered hammer (10) to rise and strike the string(s) (16).
[src:accordion/action-piano] Simultaneously, the rising end of the key also lifts the spoon (14), which is connected to a felt block called the damper (15), which normally rests on the string(s), preventing vibrations.
[src:accordion/action-piano] With the damper lifted, the string(s) vibrate after the hammer has struck them.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The short end of the jack is tripped by the letoff button (4) just before the moment the hammer strikes the string(s), causing the long end of the jack to slip off the knuckle; the hammer continues to rise and strike the string(s) by inertia, but then the hammer rebounds and falls back down.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In this way, the felt hammer is prevented from dampening the vibrations after striking the string(s), as it would if it remained in contact with the string(s).
[src:accordion/action-piano] When the key is released, the damper falls back to its resting position, silencing the note.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The damper pedal, also known as the sustain pedal, lifts the damper tray (13), which raises all of the dampers simultaneously, causing the notes to be sustained even after the keys are released.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Similar to the grand action, in an upright, when the player depresses one end of the key (12), the end on the other side of the pivot point rises.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The capstan (13) is on the rising side of the key.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The rising capstan lifts the wippen (14), which is connected to the L-shaped jack (17).
[src:accordion/action-piano] The rising wippen and jack push on the hammer butt (8) near the pivot point of the hammer shank, causing the felt-covered hammer (21) to move toward and strike the string(s) (5).
[src:accordion/action-piano] The hammer is normally held away from the string(s) by a spring near its pivot and the hammer butt.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The mechanism to move the damper off the string(s) for the upright action differs from the grand action.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In the upright action, the wippen has a pivot on the main rail (9); as the jack end of the wippen rises for the hammer strike, the other end of the wippen falls, pushing the connected spoon (11) toward the string(s).
[src:accordion/action-piano] The moving spoon in turn pushes on the damper arm (7), which also pivots on the main rail, lifting the connected damper (6) from the string(s); the damper is held in place normally by a spring on the damper arm, preventing vibrations.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The return motion of the hammer as it rebounds from the string(s) is assisted by the catcher and bridle, which is a flexible strap (generally leather) connecting the catcher to the wippen; the bridle adds the weight of the wippen to the hammer to help the hammer return to the back check.
[src:accordion/action-piano] When the key is released, the damper is restored to its resting position by a spring, silencing the note, and the hammer returns to its initial resting position on the hammer rail (20).
[src:accordion/action-piano] If the damper or sustain pedal is depressed, that action lifts a bar (10), which moves all of the dampers off the strings simultaneously, causing notes to be sustained even after the keys are released.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The Zumpe action, as fitted to his square pianos from c.
[src:accordion/action-piano] 1765, is fairly straightforward: as the key (1) is depressed, the rising end of the lever raises the leather-covered jack (2), also known as the "old man's head".
[src:accordion/action-piano] This in turn lifts the hammer, which is hinged using a leather strap, to strike the string(s) above it.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Simultaneously, the damper (6) is lifted from the string(s) by the damper jack (5), also known as the "mopstick".
[src:accordion/action-piano] In the Viennese action, when the player depresses one end of the seesaw-like key (1), the end on the other side of the pivot point rises, lifting the fork (18).
[src:accordion/action-piano] The end of the hammer butt (17) is constrained by the hopper (16), so as the fork rises, the hammer shank (21) effectively pivots at the hammer butt and the hammer (3) is raised toward and strikes the string(s) (7).
[src:accordion/action-piano] Simultaneously, the rising end of the key also lifts the damper capstan (19), which is connected via the transfer wire (20) to a felt block called the damper (10), which normally rests on the string(s), preventing vibrations.
[src:accordion/action-piano] Since the felt hammer itself would dampen these vibrations if it remains in contact with the string(s), a hammer escapement is provided by the notched rising end of the key, which engages with a structure analogous to the letoff button just before the hammer strikes the string.
[src:accordion/action-piano] This letoff button is attached to the hopper, which is hinged and held in place normally by the spring slide wire (15).
[src:accordion/action-piano] The rising end of the key tilts the hopper against the spring, towards the rear of the piano, causing the hopper to disengage from the hammer butt; the hammer continues to rise until it strikes the string(s), then it rebounds and falls back down.
[src:accordion/action-piano] If the key remains depressed, the hammer is held above its initial resting position by the back check (2); this facilitates rapid repetition of notes.
[src:accordion/action-piano] When the key is released, the damper falls back to its resting position, silencing the note, and the hammer returns to its initial resting position.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The damper guide rail (8) is lifted by the damper pedal, allowing multiple sustained notes.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The action mechanism of a key consists of the key itself and all its appurtenances.
[src:accordion/action-piano] These appurtenances include a see-saw like leverage-system, the escapement, a supplementary device for repetition, and a check for hammer rebound.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The illustration to the right is of a circa 1907 Wessell, Nickel and Gross upright action; the parts are listed below.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In a typical hammer action keybed for a digital piano, as the key (1) is depressed, a cam (4) underneath the key presses on one end of a hammer (5), lifting the hammer weight (6) on the other end.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The sensor(s) (7) in this case are placed to detect the motion of the hammer; sensors may be placed to detect key and/or hammer position, force, and velocity.
[src:accordion/action-piano] The shape, size, and weight of the hammer affects the touch of the key, as does the placement of the sensor(s), pivots (8), and the design of the mechanical linkage between the key cam and the hammer.
[src:accordion/action-piano] A retaining hook (2) with a cushion is provided so the key does not rise above its resting position.
[src:accordion/action-piano] To make the keybed more compact, many digital keyboards use a pivot point in the rear and hammers underneath the keys, as illustrated.
[src:accordion/action-piano] In the interest of replicating the feel of an acoustic grand piano, some electronic keyboards use a longer key, in some cases moving the pivot point to the middle and relocating the hammer weight and sensor above the key.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He was born in Tolna, Kingdom of Hungary, then part of the Habsburg Monarchy and shortly after made part of the Austrian Empire; his original name was Schmid.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] His parents died when he was young, and he grew up with his aunt and uncle in Brno.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] His early music lessons were from Joseph Rieger, organist at the Church of St James in Brno.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] Aged eight he played piano in public concerts; later, helped by his uncle, he appeared in theatres as singer and actor.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He was also interested in composition and composed songs and piano pieces.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] There he studied composition with Joseph von Blumenthal.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] His first operetta *Wer andern eine Grube gräbt, fällt selbst hinein* ("He who digs a hole for another, falls into it himself") was produced in December 1825 at the Theater in der Josefstadt; in the following year his operetta *Die schwarze Frau* was produced, and was very successful.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He was engaged in 1826 as a singer in the court opera ensemble at the Theater am Kärntnertor.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He composed for this theatre the operetta *Die erste Zusammenkunft*; as a result he became conductor at the theatre, and a new operetta was commissioned.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] In 1827 he was one of the pallbearers at Beethoven's funeral.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] In 1828 Müller gave up stage performing, and became composer and conductor at the Theater an der Wien, for the theatre manager Carl Carl; during the following years he composed much music.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] In 1838 Carl Carl bought the Theater in der Leopoldstadt, and Müller also worked for that theatre.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] From 1847 he left the Theater in der Leopoldstadt and worked at the Theater an der Wien, which by then was managed by Franz Pokorny.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He continued to compose; his works were performed in many theatres in Vienna.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He wrote a great amount of music for the plays of Johann Nestroy, Ludwig Anzengruber and others; Müller's music was an influence on the development of Viennese operetta.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He also wrote a large number of songs with piano accompaniment, and several works for piano and for physharmonica.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] (1839–1901) conducted the opera orchestra in Posen (now Poznań in Poland) in 1864, and later worked in Magdeburg, Düsseldorf, Rotterdam and at the Theater an der Wien in Vienna, where he initially assisted his father.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He composed operas, operettas, Singspiele and incidental music to plays.
[src:accordion/adolf-müller-sr] He compiled the music for the operetta *Wiener Blut* from existing music by Johann Strauss II.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's success has been attributed to his effective use of music videos to further parody pop culture, the songs' original artists, and the original music videos themselves.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He has directed some of his own music videos and also directed music videos for other artists including Ben Folds, Hanson, the Black Crowes, and the Presidents of the United States of America.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] With the decline of music television and the onset of social media, he used YouTube and other video sites to publish his videos; this strategy helped boost sales of his later albums.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He has not released a full album since *Mandatory Fun*, opting instead for timely releases of singles.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's work has earned him five Grammy Awards and a further eleven nominations, four gold records and six platinum records in the U.S.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] His first top ten *Billboard* album (*Straight Outta Lynwood*) and single ("White & Nerdy") were both released in 2006, nearly three decades into his career.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] His fourteenth studio album, *Mandatory Fun* (2014), became his first number-one album during its debut week.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In addition to his music career, Yankovic wrote and starred in the film *UHF* (1989) and the television series *The Weird Al Show* (1997).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He has produced two satirical films about his own life, *The Compleat Al* (1985) and *Weird: The Al Yankovic Story* (2022).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He has appeared in various television shows and web series, in addition to starring in *Al TV* specials on MTV.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He has also written two children's books, *When I Grow Up* (2011) and *My New Teacher and Me!* (2013).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Alfred Matthew Yankovic was born in Downey, California, on October 23, 1959, the only child of Mary Elizabeth (née Vivalda, 1923–2004) and Nick Yankovic (1917–2004).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He was raised in nearby Lynwood, California.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Nick Yankovic began living in California after earning two Purple Hearts for his service as a medic during World War II.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He believed "the key to success" was "doing for a living whatever makes you happy" and often reminded his son of this philosophy.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's mother, a stenographer from Kentucky of English and Italian descent, married his father in 1949.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] She moved to California a decade before Yankovic was born.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's first accordion lesson, which sparked his interest in music, took place on the day before his seventh birthday.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] A door-to-door salesman traveling through Lynwood offered his parents a choice of accordion or guitar lessons at a local music school.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic claims that his parents chose the accordion over the guitar because "they figured there should be at least one more accordion-playing Yankovic in the world"; this was in reference to Frankie Yankovic, to whom he is not related.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He has also said that they chose the accordion because "they were convinced it would revolutionize rock".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Since his mother did not let him outside the house often, he had plenty of time to practice the instrument at home.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He continued lessons at the music school for three years before deciding to continue learning on his own.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In the 1970s, Yankovic was a big fan of Elton John and cites John's 1973 album *Goodbye Yellow Brick Road* as one of the reasons he "learned to play rock 'n' roll on the accordion".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] As for his influences in comedy and parody music, he has listed artists including Stan Freberg, Spike Jones, Tom Lehrer, Allan Sherman, Shel Silverstein, and Frank Zappa, as well as "all the other wonderfully sick and twisted artists" he found through *The Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Other sources of inspiration for his comedy came from *Mad* magazine, the British comedy troupe Monty Python, and the Zucker, Abrahams and Zucker films.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He had also enjoyed George Carlin's stand-up comedy album *FM & AM* so much that he transcribed it by typewriter.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He graduated in 1976, and was valedictorian of his senior class.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He attended California Polytechnic State University in San Luis Obispo, earning a bachelor's degree in architecture.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] After graduation, he worked at Westwood One, first in the mail room and then calling stations confirming that paid advertisements had indeed run on air.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's music received its first on-air exposure via syndicated comedy radio personality Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Demento's Southern California–based show, later saying, "If there hadn't been a Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Demento, I'd probably have a real job now." Despite his mother having caught him listening to Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Demento's program and banning him from listening to it again, he found ways to do it discreetly.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Demento spoke at Yankovic's school, where the 16-year-old gave him a homemade cassette tape of original and parody songs on accordion and recorded in Yankovic's bedroom into a "cheesy little tape recorder".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The tape's first song, "Belvedere Cruisin' "(about his family's Plymouth Belvedere) was played on Demento's radio show, launching Yankovic's career.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic also played at local coffeehouses, accompanied by fellow dorm resident Joel Miller on bongos.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] During Yankovic's second year as an architecture student at Cal Poly, San Luis Obispo, he became a disc jockey at KCPR, the university's radio station.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic had been called "Weird Al" originally as a more derogatory nickname by others in his dormitory, since he was seen as the strange outcast compared to other residents.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Though he initially took it as an insult, Yankovic eventually "took it on professionally" as his persona for the station.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 1978, he released his first recording (as Alfred Yankovic), "Take Me Down", on the LP *Slo Grown*, as a benefit for the Economic Opportunity Commission of San Luis Obispo County.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The song mocked famous nearby landmarks such as Bubblegum Alley and the waterfall toilets at the Madonna Inn.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In mid-1979, shortly before his senior year, "My Sharona" by the Knack was on the charts.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic took his accordion into the restroom across the hall from the radio station to take advantage of the echo chamber acoustics and recorded a parody titled "My Bologna".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Demento, who played it to a positive listener response.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic met the Knack after a show at his college and introduced himself as the author of "My Bologna".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The Knack's lead singer, Doug Fieger, said he liked the song and suggested that Capitol Records vice president Rupert Perry release it as a single.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] "My Bologna" was released with "School Cafeteria" as its B-side, and the label gave Yankovic a six-month recording contract.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic, who was "only getting average grades" in his architecture degree, began to realize that he might make a career of comedic music.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] On September 14, 1980, Yankovic was a guest on *The Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Demento Show*, where he was to record a new parody live.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The song was called "Another One Rides the Bus", a parody of Queen's hit "Another One Bites the Dust".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] While practicing the song outside the sound booth, he met Jon "Bermuda" Schwartz, who told him he was a drummer and agreed to bang on Yankovic's accordion case to help Yankovic keep a steady beat during the song.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] They rehearsed the song just a few times before the show began.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] "Another One Rides the Bus" became so popular that Yankovic's first television appearance was a performance of the song on *The Tomorrow Show* with Tom Snyder on April 21, 1981.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] On the show, Yankovic played his accordion, and again, Schwartz banged on the accordion case and provided comical sound effects.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's record label, TK Records, went bankrupt about two weeks after the single was released, so Yankovic received no royalties from its initial release.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 1981, Yankovic went on tour for the first time as part of Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] His stage act in a Phoenix, Arizona, nightclub caught the eye of manager Jay Levey, who was "blown away".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Levey asked Yankovic if he had considered creating a full band and doing his music as a career.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic admitted that he had, so Levey held auditions.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Steve Jay became Yankovic's bass player, and Jay's friend Jim West played guitar.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's first show with his new band was on March 31, 1982.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Several days later, Yankovic and his band were the opening act for Missing Persons.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic recorded "I Love Rocky Road" (a parody of "I Love Rock 'n' Roll" originally recorded by The Arrows), which was produced by Rick Derringer, in 1982.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The song was a hit on Top 40 radio, leading to Yankovic's signing with Scotti Brothers Records.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 1983, Yankovic's first self-titled album was released on Scotti Bros.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The song "Ricky" (a parody of Toni Basil's hit "Mickey") was released as a single and the music video received exposure on the still-young MTV.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] "Ricky" broke the top 100 videos on MTV at the time, which Yankovic took as a sign that his career was in music, quitting his job as a mailroom clerk at the local offices of Westwood One to pursue the music career.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic released his second album *"Weird Al" Yankovic in 3-D* in 1984.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The first single "Eat It", a parody of the Michael Jackson song "Beat It", became popular, thanks in part to the music video, a shot-for-shot parody of Jackson's "Beat It" music video, and what Yankovic sarcastically described as his "uncanny resemblance" to Jackson.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic said he felt he had become an overnight success once the video for "Eat It" aired on MTV, as both the song and video, as well as Jackson's approval for the parody, drew attention to him from other musicians and made it easier for him to obtain permissions to use others' songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] "Eat It" was also aided by the first of Yankovic's *Al TV* specials that aired on MTV on April 1, 1984, the network looking to Yankovic's rising popularity to help fill its programming time.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] 12 on the *Billboard* Hot 100 on April 14, 1984, "Eat It" remained Yankovic's highest-charting single until "White & Nerdy" placed at No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 1985, Yankovic co-wrote and starred in a mockumentary of his own life titled *The Compleat Al* (the title being a parody of the 1982 documentary *The Compleat Beatles*), which intertwined the facts of his life up to that point with fiction.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The film also featured some clips from Yankovic's trip to Japan and some clips from the *Al TV* specials.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] *The Compleat Al* was co-directed by Jay Levey, who would direct *UHF* four years later.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Also released around the same time as *The Compleat Al* was *The Authorized Al*, a biographical book based on the film.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The book, resembling a scrapbook, included real and fictional humorous photographs and documents.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic and his band toured as the opening act for the Monkees in mid-1987 for their second reunion tour of North America.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic claims to have enjoyed touring with the Monkees, even though he said that the promoter cheated them out of "a bunch of money".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 1988, Yankovic was the narrator on the Wendy Carlos recording of Sergei Prokofiev's *Peter and the Wolf*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The album also included a sequel to Camille Saint-Saëns's composition *The Carnival of the Animals*, titled "The Carnival of the Animals Part II", with Yankovic providing humorous poems for each of the featured creatures in the style of Ogden Nash, who had written humorous poems for the original.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] That year, Yankovic made his theatrical film debut with a cameo appearance in the film *Tapeheads*, starring as himself.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] This was followed by a cameo appearance in *The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!*, also in 1988.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's success led to a deal to make his film *UHF*, which premiered in July 1989.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] While the film has since become a cult title, its initial release was against mediocre reviews, and it was up against several other summer blockbusters, including *Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade*, *Ghostbusters II*, *Batman*, and *Licence to Kill*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] While Yankovic released an associated soundtrack album, *UHF – Original Motion Picture Soundtrack and Other Stuff*, it was not as successful as his previous albums.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic fell into a slump over the next three years as a result of the poor performance of the film.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic had returned to the studio to prepare songs for his next album *Off the Deep End* around 1990.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] During production, Rubén Valtierra joined the band on keyboards in 1991, allowing Yankovic to concentrate more on singing and increasing his use of the stage space during concerts.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Further, Yankovic took over production from Rick Derringer in 1992.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] While Derringer had produced six of Yankovic's previous albums, for which he won two Grammy Awards, Derringer's drug-related issues had become a problem, along with Yankovic's increasingly more complex musical vision (involving horns and other instruments).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] By 1992, most of the original songs for *Off the Deep End* were complete, but Yankovic still did not have a strong parody and was waiting for the next big hit to work from, as he was still in a slump post-*UHF*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] When Jackson released his next album, *Dangerous*, and its hit single "Black or White", Yankovic had quickly written a parody, "Snack All Night", from it, and hoped Jackson would allow him to use the parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Jackson denied Yankovic this, as Jackson felt "Black or White" carried a serious message that would be undermined by the parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Around this time, Nirvana and the grunge music scene began to take off.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic wrote a parody of Nirvana's hit "Smells Like Teen Spirit", "Smells Like Nirvana", and was able to secure the band's permission for the parody; Nirvana's lead singer Kurt Cobain reportedly said that getting Yankovic to parody their work was a sign their band had "made it".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] "Smells Like Nirvana" became the lead song on *Off the Deep End*, landing at No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] 35 on the *Billboard* charts, his second top-40 hit in the United States.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] 17 on the *Billboard* 200, and helped to revitalize Yankovic's career after the failure of *UHF*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic's next two studio albums were modest successes in light of *Off the Deep End*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] *Alapalooza* was released in 1993, and led with "Jurassic Park", a spoof of "MacArthur Park" by Richard Harris while mocking the 1993 film of the same name.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] *Bad Hair Day* in 1996 headlined with "Amish Paradise", a parody of Coolio's "Gangsta's Paradise".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] 53 on the top *Billboard* Hot 100 singles, while the album reached No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] 14 on the *Billboard* 200, and eventually was certified double platinum in sales by RIAA, making it one of Yankovic's more successful works.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In addition, Yankovic released a number of compilation works during this period, including *Permanent Record: Al in the Box*, a four-CD collection which included most of Yankovic's previous works as well as an informational booklet with contributions from Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Other compilations included *Greatest Hits Volume II*, a collection of songs that were not included on *Permanent Record*, and *The TV Album*, featuring songs loosely based on television shows.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] On January 23, 1998, Yankovic had LASIK eye surgery to correct his extreme myopia.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic had the surgery for free when he agreed to let KTLA Morning News broadcast it live on television.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] When *Running with Scissors* debuted in 1999, he unveiled a radically changed look.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In addition to shedding his glasses, he had shaved off his moustache and grown out his hair.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He had previously shaved his moustache in 1983 for the video of "Ricky" to resemble Desi Arnaz, in 1989 for segments of the "UHF" music video and in 1996 for the "Amish Paradise" video.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic reasoned, "If Madonna's allowed to reinvent herself every 15 minutes, I figure I should be good for a change at least once every couple of decades." He parodied the reaction to this "new look" in a commercial for his nonexistent *MTV Unplugged* special.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The commercial featured Yankovic in the short-haired wig from the music video for Hanson's "River", claiming his new look was an attempt to "get back to the core of what I'm all about", that being "the music".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Following *Straight Out of Lynwood*, Yankovic started to explore digital distribution of his songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] On October 7, 2008, Yankovic released to the iTunes Store "Whatever You Like", a parody of the T.I. song of the same title, which Yankovic said he had come up with two weeks before.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] These five digitally released songs were packaged as a digital EP titled *Internet Leaks*, with "Whatever You Like" retroactively included in the set.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 2011, Yankovic completed his thirteenth studio album, titled *Alpocalypse*, which was released on June 21, 2011.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The album contains the five songs from the previous *Internet Leaks* digital download release, a polka medley called "Polka Face", a song called "TMZ", for which Bill Plympton created an animated music video, and five other new songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic had reported an interest in parodying Lady Gaga's material, and on April 20 announced that he had written and recorded a parody of "Born This Way" titled "Perform This Way" to be the lead single for his new album.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] However, upon first submitting it to Lady Gaga's manager for approval (which Yankovic does as a courtesy), he was not given permission to release it commercially.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] As he had previously done under similar circumstances (with his parody of James Blunt's "You're Beautiful", which was titled "You're Pitiful"), Yankovic then released the song for free on the internet.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Soon afterwards, Gaga's manager admitted that he had denied the parody of his own accord without forwarding the song to his client, and upon seeing it online, Lady Gaga granted permission for the parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic has stated that all of his proceeds from the parody and its music video will be donated to the Human Rights Campaign, to support the human rights themes of the original song.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic was also a judge for the 10th annual Independent Music Awards to support independent artists' careers.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic stated in September 2013 that he was working on a new album, and in 2014, he used social media websites to hint at a July 15 release of the new album.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The album artwork and title, *Mandatory Fun*, were confirmed by his publisher.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] *Mandatory Fun* was released to strong critical praise and was the No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] 1 debut album on the *Billboard* charts the week of its release, buoyed by Yankovic's approach for releasing eight music videos over eight continuous days that drew viral attention to the album as described below.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Additionally, the song "Word Crimes" (a parody of Robin Thicke's "Blurred Lines") reached No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] 39 on the Top 100 singles for the same week; this is Yankovic's fourth Top 40 single (following "Eat It", "Smells Like Nirvana", and "White & Nerdy") and made him the third musical artist, after Michael Jackson and Madonna, to have a Top 40 single in each decade since the 1980s.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In an interview promoting *Mandatory Fun*, Yankovic said that, with the end of his recording contract, he was unlikely to release any more albums, in the sense of recording and releasing that many songs at a time.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Instead, he said he would likely switch to releasing singles and EPs over the Internet, allowing him to release music faster, particularly parodies that that can quickly become dated.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He has released no albums, and indeed, few songs, since *Mandatory Fun*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In a 2017 interview, he told *Rolling Stone*, "I can't tell you when any material is coming out.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Inspiration could strike tomorrow and I might have something out next month.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] After several years of fan-driven campaigns, Yankovic received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame in 2018.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In March 2018, Yankovic released "The Hamilton Polka", a medley of several songs from the musical *Hamilton* written by Lin-Manuel Miranda.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic and Miranda had met and become friends before the latter's work on *Hamilton* and had discussed a possible music project together.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] After the success of *Hamilton*, Miranda provided Yankovic the score from the musical, hoping that Yankovic would create a few singles from it, but Yankovic ultimately created a full polka medley.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The song was the first polka to chart on Billboard's Digital Songs Sales Chart.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] After *Hamilton* premiered on Disney+ in July 2020, Yankovic released a video version of "The Hamilton Polka" that synched his song to video clips from the show.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Also in March, Yankovic released two remixes of songs by Portugal.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The Man: "Feel It Still" and "Live in the Moment".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 2020, he collaborated with the band on their single "Who's Gonna Stop Me", which was released for Indigenous Peoples' Day.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Since *Mandatory Fun*, Yankovic has focused less on new songs than on projects such as his tours and the 2022 parody biopic *Weird: The Al Yankovic Story*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] That year, Yankovic told the *Los Angeles Times* that he was not writing many new parodies because it had become harder to tell which new songs would be big hits, due to what the newspaper described as popular music trending more towards "micro-niche[s]" than a "monoculture".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic released a new polka medley, "Polkamania!", on July 19, 2024, featuring his take on "Flowers", "Bad Guy", and "Old Town Road", among others.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Because he had not released a polka in ten years, he considered this the opportunity to include his "white whales", though limited the songs to those that reached No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] The single included the release of video created by several animators that Yankovic had worked with in past videos, such as Bill Plympton, Augenblick Studios, Liam Lynch, and Jarrett Heather as well as new collaborations with artists like Cyriak and Vivienne Medrano.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic co-headlined Riot Fest in September 2025 Chicago along with Green Day, Blink-182, Jack White, Weezer, and Idles.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic married Suzanne Krajewski, a marketing executive with 20th Century Fox, after they met in 2001.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] They were introduced to each other on a blind date by their mutual friend Bill Mumy.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] They live in Los Angeles, where they own a house previously owned by writer Jack S.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In contrast to his stage persona, Yankovic is known by friends and associates to be polite, shy, and introverted, even among family.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He is a Christian, and a married couple from the church he attends can be seen in the background on the cover of his album *Poodle Hat*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] His religious upbringing is reflected in his abstinence from profanity, alcohol, and drugs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] On April 9, 2004, Yankovic's parents were found dead at their home in Fallbrook, California, the victims of accidental carbon monoxide poisoning from their fireplace.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Hours after his wife notified him of this, he made the decision to go on with his concert in Appleton, Wisconsin.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He later said, "Since my music had helped many of my fans through tough times, maybe it would work for me as well ... it would at least give me a break from sobbing all the time." Their deaths occurred following the release of *Poodle Hat*, which was Yankovic's lowest-selling album in 20 years.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] He considered the Appleton show and subsequent tour dates therapeutic: "If I didn't have anything to distract me, I probably would have spiraled into an even deeper depression.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Yankovic became a vegetarian in 1992 when his girlfriend gave him a copy of the 1987 John Robbins book *Diet for a New America*, which he said "made a very compelling argument for a strict vegetarian diet".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] In 1998, Yankovic underwent LASIK eye surgery to correct his near-sightedness.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] As his glasses were part of his signature look prior to the surgery, Yankovic considered wearing fake glasses but decided against it.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p01] Around this time, he had also decided to shave off his trademark mustache.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic is well known for creating parodies of contemporary radio hits, which typically make up about half of his studio releases.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Unlike other parody artists such as Allan Sherman, Yankovic and his band strive to keep the backing music in his parodies the same as the original, transcribing the original song by ear and re-recording the song for the parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic's career in novelty and comedy music has outlasted many of his "mainstream" parody targets, such as Toni Basil, MC Hammer, and Men Without Hats.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic's continued success (including the top 10 single "White & Nerdy" and album *Straight Outta Lynwood* in 2006) has enabled him to escape the one-hit wonder stigma often associated with novelty music.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic considers his body of work to primarily feature parodies, rather than satires of the original song or artist, as he found that satire of songs or artists has already been done before.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Most Yankovic songs consist of the original song's music, with a separate, unrelated set of amusing lyrics.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic's parodies are often satirical of popular culture, including television (*see The TV Album*), films ("The Saga Begins"), and food (*see The Food Album*).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic claims he has no intention of writing "serious" music.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In his reasoning, "There's enough people that do unfunny music.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic considered that his first true satirical song was "Smells Like Nirvana", which references unintelligible lyrics in Nirvana's "Smells Like Teen Spirit".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic is the sole writer for all his songs and, for "legal and personal reasons", does not accept parody submissions or ideas from fans.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] There exists, however, one exception to this rule: Madonna was reportedly talking with a friend and rhetorically asked when Yankovic was going to turn her "Like a Virgin" into "Like a Surgeon".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Madonna's friend was a mutual friend of Yankovic's manager, Jay Levey, and eventually Yankovic himself heard the story from Levey.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In writing his parodies as well as his original songs, Yankovic spends a great deal of time in deciding the right words that not only match the beat of the original song but that fit the theme of the parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He says that the lyrics of some songs have taken him weeks to write as he permutes the various choices, sometimes entering a "zombie phase" as he mulls these over in his home.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] For example, Yankovic believes he could have written a completely different version of "White & Nerdy" based on the alternative choices of lyrics he had come up with and had discarded for the final song.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He has also done significant research for other song parodies to get facts and keywords for certain areas of knowledge, such as for "I Think I'm a Clone Now" or hospitals for "Like a Surgeon".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has documented all these past lyrical attempts, first through binders and then computerized in case he needs to go back for future songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Most of Yankovic's studio albums include a polka medley of about a dozen contemporary songs at the time of the album, with the choruses or memorable lines of various songs juxtaposed for humorous effect.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In Yankovic's early career, before recording his first album, he had performed such polka medleys in live shows in California, though then using songs from lesser-known bands like Bad Brains and the Plasmatics.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He had been inspired to do so from Spike Jones, who had transitioned from classical music into polka.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic said that converting these songs to polka was "...the way God intended".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic did not include a medley on his first album, but considered this for his second, *In 3-D*, recognizing that it would only work if he used well-known songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The resulting "Polkas on 45", which featured songs from Devo, Deep Purple, Berlin, and The Beatles, was popular, and the polka medley became a staple of all but one of Yankovic's future albums.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic said that "fans would be rioting in the streets, I think, if I didn't do a polka medley." More current polka medleys feature songs that Yankovic had wanted to parody but which had proved difficult, such as Daft Punk's "Get Lucky", which lacked sufficient lyrics to parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The polkas are recorded in studio, including the sound effects which are performed live during recording, which Yankovic considered one of his favorite parts of recording.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 2018, Yankovic created a medley of songs from the musical *Hamilton*, "The Hamilton Polka".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has recorded numerous original humorous songs, such as "You Don't Love Me Anymore" and "One More Minute".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Many of these songs are style pastiches of specific bands with allusions to specific songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] For example, "First World Problems" from *Mandatory Fun* is a style take on Pixies, with the opening stanza reminiscent of Pixies' "Debaser".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Other style parodies includes those of Rage Against the Machine with "I'll Sue Ya" (which features many aspects of the hit song "Killing in the Name"), Devo with "Dare to Be Stupid", The B-52's with "Mr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Popeil", Talking Heads with "Dog Eat Dog", Frank Zappa with "Genius in France", Nine Inch Nails with "Germs", and Queen with "Ringtone".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Some songs are pastiches of an overall genre of music, rather than a specific band (for example, country music with "Good Enough For Now", charity records with "Don't Download This Song" and college fight songs with "Sports Song").
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic stated that he does not have any unreleased original songs, instead coming up and committing to the song ideas he arrives at for his albums and other releases.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has contributed original songs to several films ("This Is the Life" from *Johnny Dangerously*; "Polkamon" from the film *Pokémon: The Movie 2000*; and a parody of the James Bond title sequence in *Spy Hard*), in addition to his own film, *UHF*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Other songs of his have appeared in films or television series as well, such as "Dare to Be Stupid" in *The Transformers: The Movie*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 2017, Yankovic made a guest appearance on *Last Week Tonight with John Oliver*, performing a new song "The North Korea Polka", as part of an episode about the political state of North Korea.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Since around 2015, most of Yankovic's output was his original works rather than parodies, with Yankovic explaining "I wanted to prove that I'm more than just the parody guy", and that there was more challenge in creating original works and pastiches.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] One of Yankovic's recurring jokes involves the number 27.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] It is mentioned in the lyrics of several songs, and seen on the covers for *Running with Scissors*, *Poodle Hat* and *Straight Outta Lynwood*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He had originally just pulled the number 27 as a random figure to use in filling out lyrics, but as his fans started to notice the reuse of the number after the first few times, he began to use 27 in his lyrics, videos, and album covers.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Other recurring jokes revolve around the names Bob (the *Al TV* interviews often mention the name, David Bowe's character in *UHF* is named Bob, and a song called "Bob", which parodies Subterranean Homesick Blues by Bob Dylan, is featured on *Poodle Hat*), Frank (e.g.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] "Frank's 2000" TV"), and the surname "Finkelstein" (e.g. the music video for "I Lost on Jeopardy", or Fran Drescher's character, Pamela Finkelstein, in *UHF*).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] A number of songs use the phrase "internal organs".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] A hamster called Harvey the Wonder Hamster is a recurring character in *The Weird Al Show* and the *Al TV* specials, as well as the subject of an original song on *Alapalooza*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Other recurring jokes include Yankovic borrowing or being owed $5.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In a number of *Al TV* interviews, he often asks if he can borrow $5, being turned down every time.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] This motif also occurs in "Why Does This Always Happen to Me?", in which his deceased friend owes him $5.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Another recurring joke is his attraction to female nostrils or nostrils in general.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] This also appears in numerous *Al TV* interviews as well as in several of his songs (such as "Albuquerque" and "Wanna B Ur Lovr").
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic also asks his celebrity guests if they could "shave his back for a nickel".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] This also appears in the song "Albuquerque".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has also put two backmasking messages into his songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] While the lyrics of Yankovic's musical parodies generally do not allude to the subject songs or artists, his music videos sometimes parody their videos.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The video for "Smells Like Nirvana" uses a set that closely resembles that of the video for Nirvana's "Smells Like Teen Spirit" and uses several of the same actors.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] This video contended with "Smells like Teen Spirit" at the 1992 MTV Video Music Awards for Best Male Video.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Other videos that draw directly from those of the original song include "Eat It", "Fat", "Money for Nothing/Beverly Hillbillies*", "Bedrock Anthem", "Bob", "Headline News", "It's All About the Pentiums", "Amish Paradise", "Like a Surgeon", and "White & Nerdy".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has said the video for "Dare to Be Stupid” parodies Devo videos in general.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Several videos include celebrity cameos.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Demento appeared in several of Yankovic's earlier videos, such as "I Love Rocky Road" and "Ricky".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The video for "I Lost on Jeopardy" includes Greg Kihn, the artist whose song, "Jeopardy", was being parodied, along with Don Pardo and Art Fleming, Jeopardy's original announcer and host, as themselves.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Florence Henderson plays an Amish seductress in "Amish Paradise".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] While most videos that Yankovic creates are aired on music channels such as MTV and VH1, Yankovic worked with animation artists to create music videos for release with extended content albums.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The DualDisc version of *Straight Outta Lynwood* features six videos set to songs from the release, including videos created by Bill Plympton and John Kricfalusi; one video, "Weasel Stomping Day" was created by the producers of the show *Robot Chicken*, and aired as a segment of that program.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] For the 2010 *Alpocalypse*, Yankovic produced videos for every song; four of those were previously released for each of the songs on the EP *Internet Leaks*, with the videos for the remaining songs released via social media sites and included in the deluxe edition of *Alpocalypse*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] These live-action and animated videos were produced by both previous collaborators such as Plympton for "TMZ", video content providers like Jib-Jab and SuperNews!, and other directors and animators.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] To help promote his 2014 album *Mandatory Fun* in social media circles, Yankovic produced eight music videos for the album releasing them over eight consecutive days with release of the album, believing it "would make an impact because people would be talking about the album all week long".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He chose to distribute the videos to different portals to avoid burdening any single one with all of the costs and work needed to produce them.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] This approach proved to be successful, as the total collection of videos had acquired more than 20 million views in the first week.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] This release strategy was considered by *The Atlantic* as a "web-enabled precision video delivery operation, and evidence of some serious digital distributional forethought" as it allows the videos to be seen by different sets of audiences for each site.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The approach was considered to be essential to promoting *Mandatory Fun* to reach the No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] 1 position on the *Billboard* charts on its debut week.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] *Businessweek* attributed the sales success of *Mandatory Fun* to the viral music video campaign.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] ABC World News elaborated that Yankovic's success is in part due to the Internet's interest in viral and humorous videos catching up with what Yankovic has been doing for his entire career.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic himself was amazed with the response he got from the album and video releases, stating that "I've been doing the same thing for 30 years and all of a sudden I'm having the best week of my life" and that he "kind of stumbled on my formula for the future".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 2025, Yankovic announced the Bigger & Weirder Tour, a concert tour featuring performances at large venues such as Madison Square Garden and the Kia Forum.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Following the release of his album *Mandatory Fun* in 2014, Yankovic has released limited new music, but the tour has seen strong ticket sales, marking it as one of his most commercially successful to date.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The tour includes elaborate performances with approximately 20 costume changes for Yankovic and nine for his band, each completed in 45 seconds or less.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The United States Supreme Court affirmed in the 1994 case *Campbell v.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.* that certain parodies (even those sold commercially) can qualify under the fair use provision of U.S. copyright law, which means that parody musicians such as Yankovic do not need to obtain permission from the original artists.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] However, as a personal rule, Yankovic has always sought permission from the original artist before commercially releasing a parody, to respect the original musicians, avoid lawsuits, and to work out agreeable royalty arrangements.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic stated of these efforts: "I don't want to hurt anybody's feelings.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] I don't want to be embroiled in any nastiness.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] I like everybody to be in on the joke and be happy for my success.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] I take pains not to burn bridges." The communications are typically handled by his manager Jay Levey, but at times Yankovic has asked the artist directly, such as flying to Denver, Colorado, to attend an Iggy Azalea concert and speak to her personally about parodying her song "Fancy".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He claims that only about two to three percent of the artists he approaches for permission deny his requests.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has stated that the holder of the publishing rights to the original song holds the publishing rights/royalties to his parodies, but that he works out an agreement to split the songwriting credit with the original songwriters.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Separately, Yankovic needs to negotiate for royalties to the original artists for including their songs within a polka medley, which is considered a cover in copyright law.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] This created difficulties in recording his first medley, "Polkas on 45", since it involved thirteen different royalty schemes, but since then, he has established a relationship with most large music publishers to easily secure the license to use their songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Many artists parodied by Yankovic have considered this as a rite of passage to show they have made it in the music industry.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Michael Jackson was a big fan of Yankovic, and Yankovic claimed Jackson "had always been very supportive" of his work.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Jackson twice allowed him to parody his songs ("Beat It" and "Bad" became "Eat It" and "Fat", respectively).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] When Jackson granted Yankovic permission to do "Fat", Jackson allowed him to use the same set built for his own "Badder" video from the *Moonwalker* film.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic said that Jackson's support helped to gain approval from other artists he wanted to parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Though Jackson allowed "Eat It" and "Fat", he requested that Yankovic not record a parody of "Black or White", titled "Snack All Night", because he felt the message was too important.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has performed a concert-only parody "Snack All Night" in some of his live shows.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic was one of several celebrities who appeared in the 1989 music video for Jackson's song "Liberian Girl".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Dave Grohl of Nirvana said that the band felt they had "made it" after Yankovic recorded "Smells Like Nirvana", a parody of the grunge band's smash hit, "Smells Like Teen Spirit".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Additionally, Cobain described Yankovic as "America's modern pop-rock genious [sic]" in his posthumously released personal notebook.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Mark Knopfler approved Yankovic's parody of the Dire Straits song "Money for Nothing" for use in the film *UHF* on the provision that Knopfler himself be allowed to play lead guitar on the parody which was later titled "Money for Nothing/Beverly Hillbillies*".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic commented on the legal complications of the parody in the DVD audio commentary for *UHF*, explaining "We had to name that song 'Money for Nothing "slash" Beverly Hillbillies "asterisk"' because the lawyers told us that had to be the name.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] What ya gonna do?" The *Permanent Record: Al in the Box* booklet referred to the song's "compound fracture of a title".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] When a fan asked about the song's title, Yankovic shared his feelings on the title, replying "That incredibly stupid name is what the lawyers insisted that the parody be listed as.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Don McLean was reportedly pleased with "The Saga Begins", a parody of "American Pie" that summarizes *Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom Menace*, and told Yankovic that the parody's lyrics sometimes enter his mind during live performances.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] His parody not only replicates the music from the original McLean song, but it replicates the multi-layered rhyming structure in the verses and chorus.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Chamillionaire was also very pleased, even putting Yankovic's parody "White & Nerdy" (a parody of "Ridin'") on his official MySpace page before it was on Yankovic's own page.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Chamillionaire stated in an interview, "He's actually rapping pretty good on it, it's crazy [...] I didn't know he could rap like that.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Gaga considered herself "a huge Weird Al fan", and she stated that the parody was a "rite of passage" for her musical career and considered the song "very empowering".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic states that his style parodies have also been met with positive remarks by the original artist.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He noted that his friends and fellow musicians Ben Folds and Taylor Hanson helped to support their respective style parodies "Why Does This Always Happen To Me?" and "If That Isn't Love".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] One of Yankovic's most controversial parodies was 1996's "Amish Paradise", based on "Gangsta's Paradise" by hip-hop artist Coolio, which, in turn, was based on "Pastime Paradise" by Stevie Wonder.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Reportedly, Coolio's label gave Yankovic the impression that Coolio had granted permission to record the parody, but Coolio maintained that he never did.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] While Coolio claimed he was upset, legal action never materialized, and Coolio accepted royalty payments for the song.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] After this controversy, Yankovic has always made sure to speak directly with the artist of every song he parodied.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] At the XM Satellite Radio booth at the 2006 Consumer Electronics Show, Yankovic and Coolio made peace.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] On his website, Yankovic wrote of this event, "I don't remember what we said to each other exactly, but it was all very friendly.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 1999, Red Hot Chili Peppers bassist Flea told *Behind the Music* that he was unimpressed and disappointed by Yankovic's 1993 song "Bedrock Anthem", which parodied the band's songs "Under the Bridge" and "Give It Away".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He was quoted as stating, "I didn't think it was very good.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] On numerous occasions, Prince refused Yankovic permission to record parodies of his songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic had stated in interviews prior to Prince's death in 2016 that he had "approached him every few years [to] see if he's lightened up".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic related one story where, before the American Music Awards where he and Prince were assigned to sit in the same row, he got a telegram from Prince's management company, demanding he not even make eye contact with the artist.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Among parodies that Yankovic had ideas for included one based on "Let's Go Crazy" about *The Beverly Hillbillies*, "Yellow Snow" as a parody of "Purple Rain", "1999" as an infomercial with a call-in number ending in −1999, and parodies of "Kiss" and "When Doves Cry".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Despite these refusals, Yankovic was able to gain permission to parody the "When Doves Cry" video as part of his music video for the song "UHF".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He later wrote "Traffic Jam" for his album *Alapalooza*, in the style of "Let's Go Crazy", without Prince's express permission.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Led Zeppelin guitarist Jimmy Page is a self-proclaimed Yankovic fan, but when Yankovic suggested the idea of creating a polka medley of Led Zeppelin songs, Page was "less than thrilled with the prospect, so [Yankovic] didn't pursue it".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic was, however, allowed the opportunity to re-record a sample of "Black Dog" for a segment of "Trapped in the Drive-Thru".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Paul McCartney, also a Yankovic fan, refused Yankovic permission to record a parody of Wings' "Live and Let Die", titled "Chicken Pot Pie", because, according to Yankovic, McCartney is "a strict vegetarian and he didn't want a parody that condoned the consumption of animal flesh".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Though McCartney suggested possibly changing the parody to "Tofu Pot Pie", Yankovic, who is also a vegetarian, found this would not fit the lyrics he had written, which featured the sound of a chicken throughout the chorus.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] While never recorded for an album, Yankovic did play parts of "Chicken Pot Pie" as part of a larger medley in several tours during the 1990s.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 2003, Yankovic was denied permission to make a video for "Couch Potato", his parody of Eminem's "Lose Yourself".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic believes that Eminem thought that the video would be harmful to his image.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 2006, Yankovic gained James Blunt's permission to record a parody of "You're Beautiful".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] However, after Yankovic had recorded "You're Pitiful", Blunt's label, Atlantic Records, rescinded this permission, despite Blunt's personal approval of the song.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The parody was pulled from Yankovic's *Straight Outta Lynwood* because of his label's unwillingness to "go to war" with Atlantic.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic released the song as a free download on his MySpace profile, as well as his official website, and plays it in concert, since it was not Blunt himself objecting to the parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic referenced the incident in his video for "White & Nerdy" when he depicts himself vandalizing Atlantic Records' Wikipedia article.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic was considering a complete polka medley with only U2 songs, but the band's publisher did not accept the terms.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Similarly, he had included Weezer's "Buddy Holly" in a polka medley, but had to pull it when the band's publisher refused to receive partial rates.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic had approached Beck asking for permission to parody his song "Loser", which Yankovic had created called "Schmoozer".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] At the time, Beck was just entering the music industry, and did not want his reputation to be seen as a one-hit wonder and refused the parody.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Beck stated in 2022 that he wished he had given Yankovic permission, saying "I think it would have been an amazing video, I'm actually really sad it didn't happen." Although the parody was refused, "Loser" was used as the opening song in "The Alternative Polka" from *Bad Hair Day*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic had planned to make a parody based on "Hedwig's Theme" from the *Harry Potter* film series, but had been refused by Warner Bros.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic said that perhaps if he did a parody based on a franchise, "it's usually better just to do it and ask for forgiveness rather than permission".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic often describes his live concert performances as "a rock and comedy multimedia extravaganza" with an audience that "ranges from toddlers to geriatrics".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Apart from Yankovic and his band performing his classic and contemporary hits, staples of Yankovic's live performances include a medley of parodies, many costume changes between songs, and a video screen on which various clips are played during the costume changes.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] A concert from Yankovic's 1999 tour, Touring with Scissors, for the *Running with Scissors* album was released on VHS in 1999 and on DVD in 2000.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Titled *"Weird Al" Yankovic Live!*, the concert was recorded at the Marin County Civic Center in San Rafael, California, on October 2, 1999.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] For legal reasons, video clips (apart from those for Yankovic's own music videos) could not be shown for the home release, and unreleased parodies were removed from the parody medley for the performance.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 2003, Yankovic toured overseas for the first time.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Before 2003, Yankovic and his band had toured only the United States and parts of Canada.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Following the success of *Poodle Hat* in Australia, Yankovic performed eleven shows in Australia's major capital cities and regional areas in October of that year.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic returned to Australia and toured New Zealand for the first time in 2007 to support the *Straight Outta Lynwood* album.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] On September 8, 2007, Yankovic performed his 1,000th live show at Idaho Falls, Idaho.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic has invited members of the 501st Legion on stage during performances of his *Star Wars*-themed songs "Yoda" and "The Saga Begins", recruiting members of local garrisons (club chapters) while on tour.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In appreciation, the 501st inducted Yankovic as a "Friend of the Legion" in September 2007.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] He performed his first ever European mini-tour, including an appearance at the All Tomorrow's Parties music festival in Minehead, England in December 2010.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic was picked to perform by the Canadian band Godspeed You!
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Black Emperor, who curated the festival's lineup.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic played three other dates in the UK around his festival appearance before performing a single date in the Netherlands.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] A second concert film, *"Weird Al" Yankovic Live!: The Alpocalypse Tour*, aired on Comedy Central on October 1, 2011, and was released on Blu-ray and DVD three days later.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The concert was filmed at Massey Hall in Toronto, Canada, during Yankovic's tour supporting the album *Alpocalypse*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] As before, video clips (apart from those for his own videos) and unreleased songs were edited out for legal reasons.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic performed George Harrison's "What Is Life" at the live-recorded George Fest (Los Angeles, 2014).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] DVD and Blu-Ray CD combos of the concert honoring Harrison became available in early 2016.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Following the release of *Mandatory Fun*, Yankovic toured across the United States, Canada, and selected overseas venues in the Mandatory World Tour from 2015 through 2016, principally featuring songs from this album.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] After taking a year off, Yankovic returned to tour in the United States and Canada from February to June 2018 in The Ridiculously Self-Indulgent, Ill-Advised Vanity Tour.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] On this tour, he performed mostly original songs (not parodies) and did not use costumes, props, or video screens.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Comedian Emo Philips was the opening act.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] A further staple of this tour was Yankovic's cover performance of a different famous song at each venue, which Yankovic stated was something he and his band enjoyed doing.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Starting in June 2019, Yankovic went on his Strings Attached Tour, where he performed every show backed by a forty-one piece orchestra assembled from local musicians.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The tour was inspired by a 2016 performance he did with the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra, which he considered a "religious experience" and sought to replicate on tour.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic had the shows open with the orchestra performing a few instrumental themes, seemingly giving the concert a high-brow quality, before he and his band entered and played his songs backed by the orchestra.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The concerts finished with a large flashy production of his *Star Wars* songs, including "The Saga Begins" and "Yoda".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic toured again in 2022, following up from his 2018 tour with the Unfortunate Return Of The Ridiculously Self-Indulgent, Ill-Advised Vanity Tour, focusing on his lesser-known songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] The tour included 133 shows, concluding with Yankovic's first performance at Carnegie Hall in October 2022.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic toured in 2025 with the Bigger and Weirder Tour, with 65 different shows, including his first ever performance at Madison Square Garden.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] With "Word Crimes" from *Mandatory Fun* debuting at No.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] 39 on the Billboard Hot 100 in 2014, Yankovic became the third musical artist after Michael Jackson and Madonna to have a song in the Top 40 of the Billboard Hot 100 over each decade since the 1980s, his other Top 40 songs being "Eat It", "Smells Like Nirvana", and "White & Nerdy".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Since then, only U2 and Kenny G have also entered this group.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] 15 of the top 100 music video artists of all time in an August 2020 compilation, addressing that alongside his musical fame, "his accompanying video parodies are a vital part of the recipe".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] With his four-decade career, Yankovic's work has also influenced newer artists.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Andy Samberg of the group The Lonely Island considered Yankovic an influence during his childhood.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Lin-Manuel Miranda directly credits Yankovic as an influence on his musical *Hamilton*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Television producer Michael Schur considered that Yankovic's music represented a "deep egalitarian spirit of our culture" that allowed his comedy writers to reflect on society within his shows.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] In 2020, Mark Riedl, a researcher at Georgia Tech, created an algorithm that generates lyrics to match the rhyme and syllable schemes of preexisting songs.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p02] Yankovic" in reference to Yankovic's similar song parodies.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 1989, Yankovic starred in a feature film called *UHF*, co-written by himself and manager Jay Levey and filmed in Tulsa, Oklahoma.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] A satire of the television and film industries, also starring Michael Richards, Fran Drescher, and Victoria Jackson, it brought floundering studio Orion their highest test scores since the film *RoboCop*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] However, it was unsuccessful in theaters due to both poor critical reception and competition from other summer blockbusters at the time such as *Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade*, *Lethal Weapon 2*, *Batman* and *Licence to Kill*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The failure of the film left Yankovic in a three-year slump, which was later broken by his inspiration to compose "Smells Like Nirvana".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The film has since become a cult classic; fans bought it on eBay for high prices before it came out on DVD.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic occasionally shows clips from the film at his concerts (to which MGM, the film's current owner, initially objected in the form of a cease and desist letter).
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In an apparent attempt to make it more accessible to overseas audiences, where the term UHF is used less frequently to describe TV broadcasts, the film was titled *The Vidiot From UHF* in Australia and parts of Europe.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Demento (Patton Oswalt), falling in and out of love with Madonna (Olivia Wilde), and fading into alcoholism and being arrested, at which point his father finally admits he is "weird" as well.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic himself plays a music producer in the short.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic and Appel announced in January 2022 that they would be making a full-length biopic of the same name based on the trailer, starring Daniel Radcliffe as Yankovic, Evan Rachel Wood as Madonna, and Rainn Wilson as Dr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The film premiered at the Toronto International Film Festival in September 2022, and was released on the Roku Channel in November 2022.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The film's soundtrack album includes several re-recorded parodies featured in the film along with an original song "Now You Know".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Among other nominations and awards, the film won the Best Television Movie at the 75th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2012, Yankovic extensively featured in the sixth-season episode of *30 Rock*, "Kidnapped by Danger", in which Jenna Maroney desperately tries to come up with a "'Weird Al'-proof" song.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2014, he performed at the 66th Primetime Emmy Awards, singing a comedic medley of songs based on the themes of several Emmy-nominated shows, including *Mad Men* and *Game of Thrones*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic and Miranda appeared on the July 21, 2025, episode of *The Late Show with Stephen Colbert* a few days after news that the program would be cancelled, showing support for Colbert along with a number of guest cameos from other late night talk show hosts.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic has done voice-overs for several animated series.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He appeared in a 2003 episode of *The Simpsons*, singing "The Ballad of Homer & Marge" (a parody of John Mellencamp's "Jack & Diane") with his band.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The episode, "Three Gays of the Condo", in which Marge hires Yankovic to sing the aforementioned song to Homer in an attempt to reconcile their marriage, later won an Emmy Award for "Outstanding Animated Program (For Programming Less Than One Hour)".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He appeared in the animated Adult Swim show *Robot Chicken*, which provided him with a music video for the song "Weasel Stomping Day".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic is the voice for Squid Hat on the Cartoon Network show *The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He is also the announcer of the cartoon's eponymous video game adaptation.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He also plays local TV talent show host Uncle Muscles on several episodes of *Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!* along with other appearances on the show.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic has also supplied the voice of one-shot character 'Petroleum Joe' on *The Brak Show*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He also voiced himself on a *Back at the Barnyard* episode, and he appeared as a ringmaster who helps the regular characters of *Yo Gabba Gabba!* organize a circus in a 2007 episode of the children's show.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2011, Yankovic appeared as himself in the *Batman: The Brave and the Bold* episode "Bat-Mite Presents: Batman's Strangest Cases!" In 2012, he appeared on two episodes of *The Aquabats!
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Super Show!*, playing two different characters as the superhero SuperMagic PowerMan and as the president of the United States.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2014, he appeared in the fourth season *My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic* episode "Pinkie Pride" as Cheese Sandwich, a rival party planner to Pinkie Pie.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He later reprised his role in the season 9 episode "The Last Laugh".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2015, Yankovic voiced the supervillain Darkseid in the *Teen Titans Go!* episode "Two Parter".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He initially speaks with a deep, intimidating voice due to having a cold; after taking a lozenge, he speaks in his normal voice, and the heroes are no longer afraid of him.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Cyborg points out that Darkseid sounds like Yankovic, and the villain replies that he was "a true monster" for "undercutting musicians by subverting their words and compromising their artistic integrity".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Cyborg objects to this, and they battle.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2016, Yankovic appeared in two episodes of *BoJack Horseman* as Mr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Peanutbutter's brother, Captain Peanutbutter, and began portraying Milo Murphy in the Disney XD series *Milo Murphy's Law*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic guest voiced as Papa Kotassium in a 2016 episode of Cartoon Network's animated series, *Mighty Magiswords*, which was created by Weird Al fan, musician and accordionist Kyle Carrozza.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Carrozza sent a FAQ to Weird Al when Carrozza was in college in 1999.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Nelson as a guest on the RiffTrax audio commentary of *Jurassic Park*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] On November 10, 2009, Weird Al was a guest "internet scientist" on Rocketboom's "Know Your Meme" video series, in the installment on the topic of Auto-Tune, hosted by Jamie Wilkinson.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic later appeared in another *Funny or Die* short alongside Huey Lewis which parodied the ax murder scene in the film *American Psycho*, in which Christian Bale's character Patrick Bateman discusses the nature of Lewis's musical work before killing his victim.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] For *The Nerdist Podcast*, Weird Al began hosting a new comedic celebrity interview web series, *Face to Face with 'Weird Al' Yankovic*, on April 3, 2012.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The series features *Al TV*-esque fake interviews with film stars.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic has collobrated with the Gregory Brothers on music videos satirizing American presidential election debates.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The first music video was released in October 2016, titled "Bad Hombres, Nasty Women", shortly after the third debate between Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton, with Yankovic singing between autotuned snippets from the candidates.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic collaborated with the Gregory Brothers on a similar video, titled "We're All Doomed" after the first debate in the 2020 campaign between Trump and Joe Biden.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2024, Yankovic and the Gregory Brothers released "Deja Vu (But Worse)" about the presidential debate in June 2024 between Trump and then-candidate Joe Biden.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2018, Yankovic performed the theme song for the Dropout animated web series *Cartoon Hell*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic has directed many of his own music videos; he has directed all of his music videos from 1993's "Bedrock Anthem" to 2006's "White & Nerdy".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He also directed the end sequence of 1986's "Christmas at Ground Zero" (an original piece juxtaposing Christmas with nuclear warfare) from his *Polka Party!* album and the title sequence to *Spy Hard*, for which he sang the title song.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic wrote, directed and starred in the short 3-D film attraction "Al's Brain: A 3-D Journey Through The Human Brain", a $2.5 million project which was sponsored by and premiered at the Orange County Fair in Costa Mesa, California, in 2009.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The project included a brief cameo by Sir Paul McCartney, which Yankovic directed during McCartney's appearance at the 2009 Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Fair CEO Steve Beazley, who supported the project, considered the project a success and explored leasing the exhibit to other fairs; the second appearance of the exhibit was at the 2009 Puyallup Fair in Washington.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] He has cameo appearances in his videos for Jon Spencer Blues Explosion, Hanson (as the interviewer), and Ben Folds (as the producer fixing Folds' "shitty tracks").
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] On January 25, 2010, Yankovic announced that he had signed a production deal with Warner Bros. to write and direct a live-action feature film for Cartoon Network.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Although Yankovic previously wrote the script for *UHF*, this was to be the first film he directed.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic stated that he would not be starring in the film, as Cartoon Network wanted a younger protagonist.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] During an interview on *Comedy Death-Ray Radio*, Yankovic revealed that though Cartoon Network "loved" his script, the network decided that they were no longer intending to produce feature films.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic initially stated that he would instead shop the script around to other potential studios, but in 2013 revealed that the project had been scrapped as "it was really geared for Cartoon Network" and that he had "cannibalized jokes from that script to use for other projects".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic wrote *When I Grow Up,* a children's book released on February 1, 2011, and published by HarperCollins.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The book features 8-year-old Billy presenting to his class the wide variety of imaginative career possibilities that he is considering.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic stated that the idea for the book was based on his own "circuitous" career path.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The book allows Yankovic to apply the humorous writing style found in his music in another medium, allowing him to use puns and rhymes.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic worked with HarperCollins' editor Anne Hoppe—the first time that Yankovic has had an editor—and found her help to be a positive experience.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The book is illustrated by Wes Hargis, who, according to Yankovic, has "a childlike quality and a very fun quality and a very imaginative quality" that matched well with Yankovic's writing.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] 4 position on *The New York Times* Best Seller list for Children's Picture Books for the week of February 20, 2011.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic also wrote a sequel to *When I Grow Up*, 2013's *My New Teacher and Me!*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic became the first guest editor for *Mad* magazine for their 533rd issue, published in April 2015.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic partnered with Z2 Comics to produce *The Illustrated Al: The Songs of "Weird Al" Yankovic*, which was released on January 19, 2023.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The book takes twenty of Yankovic's songs and illustrates them in comic form, each by different artists.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic selected artists for the book based on past experience in working with the artists, but short of proofing the final work, was otherwise hands-off for various editorial choices.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Following publication of *The Illustrated Al*, Yankovic started working with the illustrators to produce new videos for these older songs, the first which was released in January 2023.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic competed on a week of *Wheel of Fortune* taped at Disney's Hollywood Studios in March 1994.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic joined the band Hanson in their music video for "Thinking 'bout Somethin'" in which he plays the tambourine.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic contributed backing vocals for the song "Time" on Ben Folds' album *Songs for Silverman*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic was also one of many celebrities who took part in the NOH8 Campaign against Proposition 8, which banned same-sex marriage in California.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic was approached by a beer company to endorse their product.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic had turned it down because he believed that "a lot of my fans were young and impressionable".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic later posted on his Twitter account that he never regretted the decision.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2009, Yankovic was a special guest on an episode of G4's *Web Soup* where he came as Mark Gormley at first.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2011, Yankovic guest starred as the character "Banana Man" in an episode of *Adventure Time*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The same year, he appeared as himself in the *How I Met Your Mother* episode "Noretta".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2012, he appeared as himself along with Alice Cooper, Bret Michaels, and Maria Menounos in *The High Fructose Adventures of Annoying Orange* for the Christmas special, and sung with Alice, Bret, and Orange.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] On May 31, 2014, Yankovic won the ACE Award (Amateur Cartoonist Extraordinaire) from the National Cartoonists Society at its awards banquet in San Diego.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] From 2014 until 2017, Yankovic appeared as a celebrity contestant in eight episodes of the game show *Celebrity Name Game*.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] On November 19, 2014, a RadioShack ad was uploaded to YouTube which featured Al in the role of a RadioShack employee.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2015, Yankovic made an appearance on an episode of *The Odd Couple* as a yoga student in the class Felix takes over for one day.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Also in 2015, Yankovic was featured as *Mad* magazine's first ever guest editor for their 533rd issue.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2016, Yankovic became the bandleader on the IFC series *Comedy Bang!
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Bang!*, on which he had previously guest starred.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In the official video for Weezer's cover of "Africa" published in September 2018, which itself is parody of Weezer's video for "Undone – The Sweater Song", Yankovic stands in for Rivers Cuomo as vocalist and lead guitar.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Though he does not appear, Yankovic is mentioned directly by name in the 2021 television series *Y: The Last Man* adapted from the 2000s comic book series of the same name, which involves a post-apocalyptic alternative timeline where all the men of the world had died.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Whereas the comic book had the characters reflect on the absence of the Rolling Stones, showrunner Eliza Clark opted to update the references for the show, and used Yankovic as a more modern artist that had been considered a great loss.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In 2025, Yankovic appeared in the music video for "Terrapin" by American indie musician Clairo, in which he plays Clairo.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The music video was directed by American actress Ayo Edebiri, marking Yankovic's first collaboration with either of them.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] With the growth of generative artificial intelligence in the 2020s, abbreviated as "AI", the "Weird Al" name has often been juxtaposed with the phrase "weird AI" which in many fonts look visually similar.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Songs posted to file-sharing networks are often misattributed to him because of their humorous subject matter.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Often, his surname is misspelled (and thus mispronounced) as "Yankovich", among other variations.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Much to the disdain of Yankovic, these misattributed files include songs that are racist, sexually explicit, or otherwise offensive.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] A young listener who had heard several of these offensive tracks by way of a file-sharing service confronted Yankovic online, threatening a boycott because of his supposedly explicit lyrics.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Quite a few of the songs, such as "Star Wars Cantina" by Mark Jonathan Davis (not, in a double misattribution, his lounge-singer character Richard Cheese), "Star Wars Gangsta Rap", "Yoda Smokes Weed", "Chewbacca", "The Devil Went to Jamaica", and several more have a *Star Wars* motif.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Some songs misattributed to him are not songs, but spoken skits, such as "Sesame Street on Crack", which is also widely misattributed to Adam Sandler.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] A list of songs frequently misattributed to Yankovic can be found at The Not Al Page and a list of all commercially released songs recorded by Yankovic can be found on his website.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In terms of legitimate parodies of Yankovic, the *Mr.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Show* sketch "Superstar Machine" features Bob Odenkirk as the character Daffy "Mal" Yinkleyankle.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic was impressed by the parody, and stated that it "zeroed in on everything that's irritating about me".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The Weird Al Star Fund was a campaign started by Yankovic's fans to get him a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Their mission was to "solicit, collect, and raise the necessary money, and to compile the information needed for the application to nominate "Weird Al" Yankovic for a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame".
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Fans worldwide have sent donations to raise the US$40,000 needed for a nomination.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In addition to the preferred method of cash donations, many methods were used to raise money for the cause, such as a live benefit show held April 11, 2006, and selling merchandise on the official website and eBay, including T-shirts, calendars, and cookbooks.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] On May 26, 2006, the campaign hit the then-$15,000 target, just five days before the May 31 deadline to submit the necessary paperwork.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] However, Yankovic was not included on the list of inductees for 2007.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] On February 9, 2007, the Hollywood Chamber Of Commerce raised the price to sponsor a new star to $25,000.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic's application was resubmitted for consideration in 2007, but he was not included among 2008's inductees.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In December 2010, the price was raised again to $30,000. and in 2017 the price was raised to $40,000.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The campaign raised the new target each time and applications continued to be submitted yearly, until The Hollywood Chamber of Commerce announced in June 2017 that Yankovic would receive a star on the Walk of Fame as one of the 2018 inductees.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In an official induction ceremony on August 27, 2018, Al received the 2,643rd star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The star is located at 6914 Hollywood Blvd, directly across the street from TCL Chinese Theatre.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The ceremony was attended by 1,500 fans.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Similar to the Weird Al Star Fund, a second fan-driven campaign called "Make the Rock Hall 'Weird'" has tried to enshrine him into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in Cleveland, Ohio, for which he has been eligible since 2004.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Previous attempts to raise awareness for the campaign and support Yankovic's nomination included a petition drive from 2006 to 2007, which raised over 9000 signatures; an art competition in 2005; additionally, a documentary film about the campaign is currently being developed.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] In addition to these efforts, an ongoing campaign is underway in which supporters of Yankovic's nomination are requested to send "sincere, thoughtful" letters to the Rock Hall Foundation's headquarters in New York.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] The Hall has not considered Yankovic for nomination since the campaign started in 2004.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] A 2009 *Rolling Stone* poll named Weird Al as the top artist that should be nominated for the Hall of Fame, followed by Rush (who were inducted in 2013) and The Moody Blues (inducted in 2018) in the top ten.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] According to the museum's chairperson John Sykes, while Yankovic has come up in various discussions on nominees, "he's never made it close to the ballot" due to the artists that vote towards the inductees.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] A smaller ongoing effort has been made by fans to have Yankovic perform at the halftime show of a Super Bowl game.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] This inspired Yankovic to write the fight song parody "Sports Song" for *Mandatory Fun* to help round out his repertoire.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic believed that he would never be selected as a standalone act for the Super Bowl, but could see other bands include him as a special guest if they were selected.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic's core band, consisting of Jon "Bermuda" Schwartz, Jim West, and Steve Jay, have performed with him for more than 40 years, and grew with the addition of Rubén Valtierra.
[src:accordion/weird-al-yankovic-p03] Yankovic credits this group as having the flexibility to play any musical genre, allowing him to perform songs across a wide range of musical styles, in addition to "we're kind of telepathic in the way we communicate now, so we're a lot better than we were back in the day".
